{"title_page": "October 1917", "text_new": "{{short description|Month in 1917}}\n{{Events by month|1917}}\n{{calendar|year=1917|month=October}}\n\nThe following events occurred in '''October 1917''':\n\n== [[October 1]], 1917 (Monday) ==\n* [[Germany]] launched [[Actions of 30 September \u2013 4 October 1917|counterattacks]] on British positions in [[Polygon Wood]], [[West Flanders]], [[Belgium]].<ref>{{cite book |title=The 23rd Division 1914\u20131919 |last=Sandilands |first=H. R. |authorlink= |year=2003 |orig-year=1925 |publisher=Wm. Blackwood |location=Edinburgh |edition=Naval & Military Press |isbn=978-1-84342-641-7|pages=200\u2013204}}</ref>\n* Eighteen Gotha bombers of the ''[[Luftstreitkr\u00e4fte]]'' (German Air Force) set out on to raid the [[United Kingdom]], with 11 of them reaching [[England]]. British [[antiaircraft gun]]s fired 14,000 rounds at them without scoring a single hit, but falling fragments from spent antiaircraft shells from the worn-out guns killed eight and injured another 67 people.<ref>Fredette, Raymond H., ''The Sky on Fire: The First Battle of Britain 1917\u20131918'', New York: Harvest, 1976, {{ISBN|0-15-682750-6}}, pp. 135, 146-147, 264.</ref>\n* [[U.S. Coast Guard]] ship [[USRC Mohawk (1904)|USS ''Mohawk'']] collided with a British cargo ship in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] off [[Sandy Hook, New Jersey]] and sank, with all 77 crew members rescued.<ref>{{cite book|last=Johnson|first=Robert Irwin|title=Guardians of the Sea, History of the United States Coast Guard, 1915 to the Present|year=1987|publisher=Naval Institute Press, Annapolis, Maryland|isbn=978-0-87021-720-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/guardiansofseahi00john/page/47 47]|url=https://archive.org/details/guardiansofseahi00john/page/47}}</ref>\n* The [[Royal Navy]] conducted the first launch of an aircraft from a [[battleship]]. [[Royal Naval Air Service]] [[Flight Commander]] [[Frederick Rutland]] took off in a [[Sopwith Pup]] fighter from a platform mounted on a 15-inch (381-mm) gun turret of the battlecruiser {{HMS|Repulse|1916|6}}.<ref>Thetford, Owen, ''British Naval Aircraft Since 1912'', Sixth Edition, Annapolis, Maryland: Naval Institute Press, 1991, {{ISBN|1-55750-076-2}}, p. 14.</ref>\n* The [[Royal Navy]] tested an [[aircraft catapult]] for the first time, using a [[compressed air|compressed-air]] catapult aboard [[HMS Slinger (1917)|''Slinger'']] to launch an unmanned [[Short 184]] aircraft in a series of trial launches.<ref>Layman, R.D., ''Before the Aircraft Carrier: The Development of Aviation Vessels 1849-1922'', Annapolis, Maryland: Naval Institute Press, 1989, {{ISBN|0-87021-210-9}}, p. 78.</ref>\n* The [[139th Infantry Regiment (United States)|139th Infantry Regiment]] of the [[U.S. Army]] was established with the merger of infantry regiments from [[Kansas]] and [[Missouri]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kenamore|first1=Clair|title=The story of the 139th infantry|url=https://archive.org/stream/storyof139thinfa00kena/storyof139thinfa00kena_djvu.txt|website=Archive.org|accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n* The [[U.S. Government]] established the [[Aircraft Board]] with [[Howard E. Coffin]] as chair.<ref>{{cite web| last =Mooney| first =Charles C. and Layman, Martha E.| year =1944| url =http://www.afhra.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-090602-051.pdf| title =Organization of Military Aeronautics, 1907-1935 (Congressional and War Department Action)| work =Air Force Historical Study No. 25| publisher =AFHRA (USAF)| accessdate =14 Dec 2010| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20101227081644/http://www.afhra.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-090602-051.pdf| archivedate =2010-12-27}}, pp. 27-29. 40 ''Stat.'' 296.</ref>\n* [[Albert Einstein]] was appointed director of the newly formed [[Kaiser Wilhelm Society|Kaiser Wilhelm Institute for Physics]] in [[Munich]] (now the [[Max Planck Institute for Physics]]).<ref>\"[https://www.mpp.mpg.de/institut/Geschichte/01_Ubersicht/index.html Geschichte] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150624040347/https://www.mpp.mpg.de/institut/Geschichte/01_Ubersicht/index.html |date=2015-06-24 }}\" (in German). Max Planck Institute for Physics. Abbreviated version in English: \"[https://www.mpp.mpg.de/english/institute/instGeschichte/Overview/index.html History] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150624042614/https://www.mpp.mpg.de/english/institute/instGeschichte/Overview/index.html |date=2015-06-24 }}.\" Retrieved 2015-08-30</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Guido Fibbia]], Italian air force officer, top fighter ace for ''[[Regia Aeronautica]]'' during [[World War Two]], two-time recipient of the [[Silver Medal of Military Valor]] and the [[Iron Cross]], in [[Treviso]], [[Italy]] (d. [[1988]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Ivan Agu\u00e9li]], Swedish artist and writer, known for his melding of [[post-impressionism]] with [[Arabic]] art following his conversion to [[Islam]] (killed in a train accident) (b. [[1869]])\n\n== [[October 2]], 1917 (Tuesday) ==\n* [[Finland]] held [[1917 Finnish parliamentary election|parliamentary elections]] with the [[Social Democratic Party of Finland]] winning 44 per cent of the vote.<ref>Thomas T Mackie & Richard Rose (1991) ''The International Almanac of Electoral History'', Macmillan, p. 243</ref>\n* [[Royal Navy]] [[armoured cruiser]] [[HMS Drake (1901)|HMS ''Drake'']] was torpedoed and sunk by German submarine {{SMU|U-79||2}} off [[Rathlin Island]] with the loss of 18 out of her 900 crew.<ref>{{cite Uboat.net|id=1713|name=HMS Drake|type=1ship|accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref>\n* The Flying Field at Anacostia, a U.S. military air base, was opened to train pilots and test new aircraft. It was renamed the Anacostia Experimental Flying Field shortly thereafter and eventually the [[Bolling Air Force Base]] after [[Colonel]] [[Raynal Bolling]] on July 1, 1918.<ref>[http://www.cnic.navy.mil/JBAB/index.htm CNIC Joint Base Anacostia-Bolling]</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Christian de Duve]], English biologist, recipient of the [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]] for his research into cell biology, in [[Thames Ditton]], [[England]] (d. [[2013]]); [[Cahal Daly]], Irish clergy, [[Archbishop of Armagh]] and [[Primacy of Ireland]] from 1990 to 1996, in [[Loughguile]], [[Ireland]] (d. [[2009]])\n* '''Born:''' [[Charles Drake (actor)|Charles Drake]], American actor, known for roles in ''[[Winchester '73]]'' and ''[[Harvey (film)|Harvey]]'', in [[New York City]] (d. [[1994]]); [[Francis Jackson (composer)|Francis Jackson]], English composer and organist, director of [[York Minster]] from 1946 to 1982, in [[Malton, North Yorkshire]], [[England]]; [[Rosaleen Norton]], New Zealand-Australian occultist, proponent of [[witchcraft]] and [[wiccanism]] in [[Sydney]], earning her the media nickname \"The Witch of Kings Cross\", in [[Dunedin]], [[New Zealand]] (d. [[1979]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Camille Tissot]], French naval officer, pioneer of [[wireless telegraphy]] (b. [[1868]])\n\n== [[October 3]], 1917 (Wednesday) ==\n* A [[Dubno Garrison Revolt|soldiers' revolt]] erupted at a garrison in [[Dubno]], [[Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web|title=1917 Dubno Garrison Revolt|url=http://leksika.com.ua/10360710/ure/dubenskogo_garnizonu_povstannya_1917|website=Ukrainian Soviet Encyclopedia|accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref>\n* German submarine {{SMU|UC-14||6}} struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and sank in the [[North Sea]] with the loss of all 14 crew.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://uboat.net/wwi/boats/index.html?boat=UC+14 |title=UC 14 |publisher=Uboat.net |accessdate=21 November 2012}}</ref>\n* The [[National Party (United States)|National Party of the United States]] held its first conference in [[Chicago]] where it formally endorsed American participation in [[World War One]].<ref>''Platform, Spirit and Aims of the National Party: Founded October 4th, 1917.'' Chicago: The National Party, 1917; pp. 11-12</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Les Schwab]], American business leader, founder of [[Les Schwab Tire Centers]], in [[Bend, Oregon]] (d. [[2007]]); [[Odd Lundberg]], Norwegian speed skater, silver and bronze medalist at the [[1948 Winter Olympics]], in [[Brandbu]], [[Norway]] (d. [[1983]])\n\n== [[October 4]], 1917 (Thursday) ==\n* [[Battle of Broodseinde]] &ndash; The [[British Second Army|British Second]] and [[British Fifth Army|Fifth Armies]], supported by the [[I ANZAC Corps]], overwhelmed [[4th Army (German Empire)|German 4th Army]]'s defenses at Broodseinde Ridge in [[West Flanders]], [[Belgium]]. Some 5,000 German troops were taken prisoner, adding to the 30,000 casualties the army suffered overall in the first 10 days of fighting in October. British suffered around 20,000 casualties, including 6,423 for [[Australia]] and 1,853 for [[New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite book |title=The Third Ypres: Passchendaele, the Day-By-Day Account |last=McCarthy |first=C. |authorlink= |year=1995 |publisher=Arms & Armour Press| location=London| edition=| isbn=978-1-85409-217-5| pages=97\u2013103}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |series=[[Official History of Australia in the War of 1914\u20131918]] |volume=IV |title=The Australian Imperial Force in France, 1917 |last=Bean |first=C. E. W. |authorlink=Charles Bean |year=1941 |orig-year=1933 |publisher=[[Australian War Memorial]] | location=Canberra |edition=online |url=https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/RCDIG1069753/ |accessdate=27 September 2014 |isbn=978-0-7022-1710-4|pages=847\u2013863}}</ref>\n* An Italian royal decree was issued allowing heavy criminal sanctions against anyone who committed or incited acts of defeatism.<ref>{{in lang|it}} [http://storia.camera.it/cronologia/leg-regno-XXIV#nav XXIV Legislatura del Regno d'Italia dal 27 novembre 1913 al 29 settembre 1919], Camera dei deputati, Portale storico (retrieved 29 May 2016)</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Violeta Parra]], Chilean folk musician, leading figure in the [[Nueva canci\u00f3n]] movement that popularized traditional Chilean music, in [[San Carlos, Chile]] (d. [[1967]]); [[Luis Carniglia]], Argentine [[association football]] player and manager, [[striker (association football)|striker]] for the [[Boca Juniors]] in the 1940s and manager for [[Real Madrid C.F.]] in the 1950s, in [[Olivos, Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]] (d. [[2001]]) \n* '''Died:''' [[Dave Gallaher]], Irish-New Zealand rugby player, team captain for [[The Original All Blacks]] and member of the [[New Zealand national rugby union team]] from 1896 to 1909 (killed in action during the [[Battle of Passchendaele]]) (b. [[1873]])\n\n== [[October 5]], 1917 (Friday) ==\n* German submarine {{SMU|UB-41||6}} struck a mine and sank in the [[North Sea]] off with the loss of all 22 crew.<ref>{{cite book| last1=Gr\u00f6ner| first1=Erich|last2=Jung|first2=Dieter| last3=Maass| first3=Martin| translator-last1=Thomas| translator-first1=Keith| translator-last2=Magowan| translator-first2=Rachel| year=1991| title=U-boats and Mine Warfare Vessels| volume=2| work=German Warships 1815\u20131945| location=London| publisher=Conway Maritime Press|isbn=0-85177-593-4|ref=CITEREFGr.C3.B6ner1991}}</ref>\n* The [[Palestine Brigade RAF|Palestine Brigade]] of the [[Royal Flying Corps]] was established to provide air support during the [[Sinai and Palestine Campaign]], which included the [[No. 40 Wing RAF|No. 40 Wing]].<ref>[http://www.rafweb.org/Wings1.htm Wing Nos 1\u201350] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080726013531/http://www.rafweb.org/Wings1.htm |date=2008-07-26 }} at [http://www.rafweb.org/Index.htm Air of Authority \u2014 A History of RAF Organisation]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071226223020/http://www.rafweb.org/Index.htm |date=26 December 2007 }}. Retrieved on 28 February 2009.</ref>\n* British politician [[Arthur Lee, 1st Viscount Lee of Fareham|Arthur Lee]] donated the country house [[Chequers]] to the British government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chilternsaonb.org/explore-enjoy/interactive-map.html#1331|title=People and history: Chequers|publisher=Chilterns Conservation Board|accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Allen Ludden]], American game show host, best known for the television game show ''[[Password (game show)|Password]]'', in [[Mineral Point, Wisconsin]] (d. [[1981]]); [[Magda Szab\u00f3]], Hungarian novelist, known for works including ''Abig\u00e9l'', in [[Debrecen]], [[Hungary]] (d. [[2007]])\n\n== [[October 6]], 1917 (Saturday) ==\n* The fourth and final [[State Duma (Russian Empire)|Duma]], the legislative assembly of the [[Russian Empire]], formally ended and was dissolved, with the [[Russian Provisional Government]] anticipating elections for the [[Russian Constituent Assembly]] to replace it.\n* The [[U.S. Government]] enacted the [[Trading with the Enemy Act of 1917|Trading with the Enemy Act]], which restricted trade with countries hostile to the [[United States]].<ref>[http://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/html/uscode12/usc_sec_12_00000095---a000-notes.html Cornell Law School]</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Marjorie Guthrie]], American choreographer, wife to folk singer [[Woody Guthrie]] and mother to [[Arlo Guthrie]], in [[Atlantic City, New Jersey]] (d. [[1983]]); [[Fannie Lou Hamer]], American activist, chief organizer of [[Freedom Summer]] for the civil rights movement, in [[Montgomery County, Mississippi]] (d. [[1977]])\n\n== [[October 7]], 1917 (Sunday) ==\n* The largest airship ever built at the time, the ''L 57'', was wrecked and destroyed by fire while trying to take off for a test flight in poor weather. The [[Zeppelin]] aircraft was 743 feet (226.5 meters) in length and could carry 2,418,700 [[cubic foot|cubic feet]] (68,490 [[cubic meters]]) of [[hydrogen gas]] for long-distance flights from [[Europe]] to [[Africa]].<ref>Whitehouse, Arch, ''The Zeppelin Fighters'', New York: Ace Books, 1966, no ISBN number, p. 234.</ref>\n* German submarine {{SMU|U-106||6}} struck a mine and sank in the [[North Sea]] with the loss of all 41 crew.<ref>{{cite Uboat.net|id=106|name=U 106|type=1sub|accessdate=25 January 2010}}</ref> \n* '''Born:''' [[June Allyson]], American actress, best known for her on-screen pairings with [[Van Johnson]] in films such as ''[[Too Young to Kiss]]'' in which she won a [[Golden Globe]], in [[New York City]] (d. [[2006]]); [[Rose Piper]], American painter, known for abstract works inspired by [[blues]] music including ''The Death of Bessie Smith'', in [[New York City]] (d. [[2005]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Serhii Vasylkivsky]], Ukrainian artist, known his prolific work on the Ukraine including the ''Cossack'' series (b. [[1854]])\n\n== [[October 8]], 1917 (Monday) ==\n* German submarine {{SMU|U-96||6}} sank British cargo ships SS ''Memphian'' and SS ''Greldon'' in [[St. George's Channel]], killing 32 and 28 crew respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/wwi/ships_hit/4073.html |title=Memphian |publisher=Uboat.net |accessdate=24 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/wwi/ships_hit/2610.html |title=Greldon |publisher=Uboat.net |accessdate=24 October 2012}}</ref>\n* German submarine {{SMU|U-57||6}} sank British cargo ship SS ''Richard de Larrinaga'' in the [[Atlantic Ocean]], killing 35 crew.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/wwi/ships_hit/5113.html |title=Richard De Larrinaga |publisher=Uboat.net |accessdate=12 October 2012}}</ref> \n* The [[Royal Flying Corps]] established air squadrons [[No. 90 Squadron RAF|No. 90]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/90squadron.cfm |title=90 Squadron |website=Royal Air Force |accessdate=8 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303220847/http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/90squadron.cfm |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and [[No. 107 Squadron RAF|No. 107]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/104squadron.cfm |title=107 Squadron |website=Royal Air Force |accessdate=8 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818132330/https://www.raf.mod.uk/history/104squadron.cfm |archive-date=2017-08-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Danny Murtaugh]], American baseball player and manager, second baseman for [[Philadelphia Phillies]], [[Boston Braves (baseball)|Boston Braves]] and [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] from 1941 to 1951, manager of the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] during the [[1960 World Series|1960]] and [[1971 World Series]], in [[Chester, Pennsylvania]] (d. [[1976]]); [[Billy Conn]], American boxer, [[Light heavyweight|world light heavyweight champion]] from 1939 to 1941, in [[Pittsburgh]] (d. [[1993]])\n* '''Born:''' [[Rodney Robert Porter]], English biochemist, recipient of the [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]] for his research on [[antibody|antibodies]], in [[Newton-le-Willows]], [[England]] (d. [[1985]]); [[Tex Banwell]], British army officer, served as political decoy for General [[Bernard Montgomery]] during [[World War Two]], in [[Newport, Essex]], [[England]] (d. [[1999]]); [[Walter Lord]], American writer, author of ''[[A Night to Remember (book)|A Night to Remember]]'', about the sinking of the [[RMS Titanic|RMS ''Titanic'']], in [[Baltimore]] (d. [[2002]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Ebenezer Ward]], Australian politician, member of the [[South Australian House of Assembly]] from 1870 to 1900 (b. [[1837]])\n\n== [[October 9]], 1917 (Tuesday) ==\n* [[Battle of Poelcappelle]] &ndash; German forces halted the British advance on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] in [[West Flanders]], [[Belgium]] but at a cost of 35,000 casualties during the first ten days of October. Total British and Commonwealth casualties for the day's fighting were around 11,500.<ref>{{cite book |series=History of the Great War Based on Official Documents by Direction of the Historical Section of the Committee of Imperial Defence |title= Military Operations France and Belgium 1917: 7 June\u201310 November Messines and Third Ypres (Passchendaele) |volume=II |last=Edmonds |first=J. E. |authorlink=James Edward Edmonds |year=1991 |orig-year=1948 |publisher=HMSO |edition=Imperial War Museum and Battery Press |location=London |isbn=978-0-89839-166-4|pages=334\u2013341}}</ref>\n* During the [[Battle of Poelcappelle]], a squad of 71 Australian soldiers with the [[10th Battalion (Australia)|10th Battalion]] [[Mystery of Celtic Wood|disappeared without a trace in Celtic Wood]] during a diversionary attack on German positions. Speculations of the unaccounted for men ranged from clerical error to the troops being massacred and buried in a mass grave (though German records made no mention of such an incident). Official Australian military document confirm at least 37 men remained unaccounted.<ref>{{citation |title=On this day: October 9 |publisher=defence.gov.au| url=http://www.defence.gov.au/army/ahu/On_This_Day/October/9_October.htm#1917 |archiveurl=http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/51715/20050801-0000/www.defence.gov.au/army/ahu/On_This_Day/October/9_October.htm#1917 |archivedate=1 August 2005}}</ref>\n* [[Royal Navy]] [[cruiser]] HMS ''Champagne'' was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Irish Sea]] by German submarine {{SMU|U-96||6}} with the loss of 58 of her 305 crew.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/wwi/ships_hit/1208.html |title=Champagne |publisher=Uboat.net |accessdate=29 December 2012}}</ref>\n* The [[U.S. Marines]] established the [[8th Marine Regiment]].<ref>[http://www.marzone.com/8thMarines/Hst2000.htm Lineage of the 8th Marine Regiment]{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* '''Died:''' [[Hussein Kamel of Egypt]], Egyptian noble, [[Sultan of Egypt]] from 1914 to 1917 (b. [[1853]]); [[Sarah Aaronsohn]], Jewish Palestinian spy, member of the [[Nili]] spy network, sister to botanist [[Aaron Aaronsohn]] (b. [[1890]])\n\n== [[October 10]], 1917 (Wednesday) ==\n* A coalition of Conservative, Liberal and independent members of [[Parliament of Canada|Canadian Parliament]] led by Prime Minister [[Robert Borden]] formed the [[Unionist Party (Canada)|Unionist Party of Canada]] to enact [[conscription]] and govern [[Canada]] through the remainder of [[World War One]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Armstrong|first1=Elizabeth|title=The Crisis of Quebec, 1914-1918|date=Jan 15, 1974|publisher=McGill-Queen's Press| location=Montreal| url=https://books.google.ca/books/about/The_Crisis_of_Quebec_1914_1918|accessdate=24 April 2016}}</ref>\n* The first novel of the science fiction series [[Barsoom]], ''[[A Princess of Mars]]'', by [[Edgar Rice Burroughs]] was published in hardcover by A.C. McClurg & Company.<ref>{{cite book |last=Porges |first=Irwin |title=Edgar Rice Burroughs |publisher=Brigham Young University Press |location=Provo, Utah |year=1975 |isbn=0-8425-0079-0 |page=[https://archive.org/details/edgarriceburroug00irwi/page/291 291] |url=https://archive.org/details/edgarriceburroug00irwi/page/291 }}</ref>\n* Norwegian sports club [[IF T\u00f8nsberg-Kameratene]] was established in [[T\u00f8nsberg]], [[Norway]] with sections for [[association football]], track and field, boxing, wrestling and weightlifting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tonsbergkameratene.no/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=26&Itemid=174|title=Litt om oss|publisher=IF T\u00f8nsberg-Kameratene|language=Norwegian|accessdate=28 July 2010}}</ref> \n* '''Born:''' [[Thelonious Monk]], American jazz musician, known for numerous jazz hits including \"[['Round Midnight (song)|'Round Midnight]]\", \"[[Blue Monk]]\", and \"[[Straight, No Chaser (composition)|Straight, No Chaser]]\", second most recorded jazz artist after [[Duke Ellington]], in [[Rocky Mount, North Carolina]] (d. [[1982]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Henry Crimmel]], American artisan, renowned glass-maker and co-founder of the [[Novelty Glass Company]] and [[Sneath Glass Company]] (b. [[1844]])\n\n== [[October 11]], 1917 (Thursday) ==\n* [[Operation Albion]] &ndash; A German amphibious force landed at [[Tagalaht]] on the island of [[Saaremaa]] in the Russian-controlled [[West Estonian archipelago]] in the [[Baltic Sea]] to capture the islands and stage a launching point to attack [[Petrograd]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Barrett |first=M. B. |url=http://www.iupress.indiana.edu/catalog/product_info.php?products_id=57467 |accessdate=24 March 2017 |title=Operation Albion: The German Conquest of the Baltic Islands |publisher=Indiana University Press |location=Bloomington, IN |year=2008 |isbn=978-0-253-34969-9|page=8}}</ref>\n* The [[Armenian National Congress (1917)|Armenian National Congress]] met in [[Tbilisi]], [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] to determine the role the Armenian population would play in post [[Imperial Russia]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Douglas|first=John M.|title=The Armenians|year=1992|publisher=J.J. Winthrop Corp.|location=New York, NY|isbn=9780963138101|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aIYlAQAAMAAJ&pg|accessdate=9 February 2013|page=358}}</ref>\n* The [[No. 41 Wing RAF|No. 41 Wing]] was established by the [[Royal Flying Corps]] with [[Lieutenant-Colonel]] [[Cyril Newall, 1st Baron Newall|Cyril Newall]] in command.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rafweb.org/Wings1.htm |title=Wing Nos 1 - 50 |accessdate=2008-07-17 |last=Barrass |first=Malcolm |date=2007-06-11 |work=Air of Authority - A History of RAF Organisation |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080726013531/http://www.rafweb.org/Wings1.htm |archivedate=2008-07-26 }}</ref>\n* The [[U.S. Army]] established the [[28th Infantry Division (United States)|28th]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/forcestruc/cbtchron/cc/028id.htm|title=Lineage and Honors Information: 28th Infantry Division |publisher=[[United States Army Center of Military History]] |accessdate=3 November 2009}}</ref> [[30th Infantry Division (United States)|30th]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/forcestruc/cbtchron/cc/030id.htm|title=Lineage and Honors Information: 30th Infantry Division |publisher=[[United States Army Center of Military History]] |accessdate=3 November 2009}}</ref> and [[31st Infantry Division (United States)|31st Infantry Divisions]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/forcestruc/cbtchron/cc/031id.htm|title=Lineage and Honors Information: 31st Infantry Division |publisher=[[United States Army Center of Military History]] |accessdate=3 November 2009}}</ref>\n* The [[Richmond Professional Institute]] was established in [[Richmond, Virginia]] as a medical and healthcare professional school.<ref>{{cite book |last = Hibbs |first = Henry |title = A History of the Richmond Professional Institute |publisher = RPI Foundation by Whittet & Shepperson |year = 1973 |page=16}}</ref>\n\n== [[October 12]], 1917 (Friday) ==\n* [[First Battle of Passchendaele]] &ndash; [[Allies of World War I|Allied]] forces failed to take key defensive ridges held by the Germans west of the village of [[Passendale|Passchendaele]], [[Belgium]].{{sfn|Edmonds|1991|pp=340\u2013344}} The brunt of the 13,000 casualties were taken by [[Australian and New Zealand Army Corps|ANZAC]] units, with the [[New Zealand]] division suffering 2,725 casualties including 845 killed, the single biggest loss for [[New Zealand]] (roughly one in 1,000 of the nation's population at that time).<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Dennis |editor1-first=P. |editor2-last=Grey |editor2-first=G. |title=1917: Tactics, Training and Technology |authorlink= |year=2007 |last=Harper |first=G. |chapter=Masterpiece or Massacre: the New Zealand Division and two Battles of 1917 |publisher=Australian History Military Publications |location=Loftus, NSW |edition= |isbn=978-0-9803-7967-9|page=69}}</ref> German casualties were estimated at 12,000.<ref>{{cite book |series=Weltkrieg 1914 bis 1918: Milit\u00e4rischen Operationen zu Lande |volume=XIII |title=Die Kriegf\u00fchrung im Sommer und Herbst 1917. Die Ereignisse au\u00dferhalb der Westfront bis November 1918 |trans-title=The War in Summer and Autumn, 1917. Events Beyond the Western Front until November, 1918 |language=German |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2012 |orig-year=1942 |publisher=Mittler |location=Berlin |url=https://digi.landesbibliothek.at/viewer/image/AC03617667/1/LOG_0003/ |accessdate=17 November 2012 |edition=Die digitale landesbibliotek Ober\u00f6sterreich |oclc=257129831 |page=96 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203013658/http://digi.landesbibliothek.at/viewer/image/AC03617667/1/LOG_0003/ |archive-date=2013-12-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Operation Albion]] &ndash; German forces captured 20,000 Russian prisoners and 100 guns as they expanded out from [[Tagalaht]] to the rest of the island of [[Saaremaa]] in the Baltic Sea.{{sfn|Barrett|2008|p=8}}\n* The first regiment was stationed at the newly commissioned Naval Operating Base in [[Norfolk, Virginia]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Hampton Roads Naval Historical Foundation|title=Images of America: Naval Station Norfolk|date=February 2014|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|location=Charleston, SC|pages=7}}</ref> \n* The Brazilian sports club [[Fonseca Atl\u00e9tico Clube|Fonseca]] was established in [[Niter\u00f3i]], [[Brazil]], and included [[association football]], martial arts, swimming and gymnastics.<ref>{{cite web| title=History| url=http://www.fonsecaatleticoclube.com.br/historia.html| website=Official Website of Fonseca Atl\u00e9tico Clube| language=Portuguese| url-status=bot: unknown| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140107192014/http://www.fonsecaatleticoclube.com.br/historia.html| archivedate=2014-01-07}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[James McAuley]], Australian poet and literary critic, known for poetry collections including ''A World of its own'' and literary criticism such as ''The rhetoric of Australian poetry'', in [[Lakemba, New South Wales]], [[Australia]] (d. [[1976]])\n* '''Died:''' [[George Augustus King]], New Zealand army officer, commander of the [[New Zealand (M\u0101ori) Pioneer Battalion|New Zealand Pioneer Battalion]] (killed at the [[Battle of Passchendaele]]) (b. [[1885]]); [[Clarence Jeffries]], Australian army officer, recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]] (killed at the [[Battle of Passchendaele]]) (b. [[1894]]); [[Lewis McGee (soldier)|Lewis McGee]], Australian soldier, recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]] for action during the [[Battle of Broodseinde]] (killed at the [[Battle of Passchendaele]]) (b. [[1888]])\n\n== [[October 13]], 1917 (Saturday) ==\n* [[Miracle of the Sun]] &ndash; A massive gathering of pilgrims in [[F\u00e1tima, Portugal]], estimated between 30,000 and 40,000 (with another report going as high as 100,000) simultaneously witnessed the sun change colors and move in impossible paths across the sky for ten minutes. The miraculous event was foretold by local children [[L\u00facia dos Santos]] and siblings [[Jacinta and Francisco Marto]], who had been experiencing visions from [[Our Lady of F\u00e1tima]] for months.<ref>{{cite book|first = John | last = De Marchi | date = 1952b | title = The Immaculate Heart, The True Story of Our Lady of Fatima| publisher = Farrar, Straus and Young | location = New York|oclc = 2947238 |pages=151\u201366}}</ref> After years of investigation, the [[Catholic Church]] concluded in 1930 that the event was genuine but skeptics have cited mass delusion brought on by weeks of speculation or meteorological illusions as the cause.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.miraclehunter.com/marian_apparitions/statements/fatima_statement_02.html|title=Results of the Investigative Commission| date=October 1930| accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Skeptoid|id=4110|number=110|title=Illuminating the Fatima Miracle of the Sun|date=July 22, 2008|accessdate=16 April 2017}}</ref>\n* Tire manufacturer [[Yokohama Rubber Company|Yokohama]] was established in [[Tokyo]] as a joint venture between Yokohama Cable Manufacturing and [[Goodrich Corporation|B.F. Goodrich]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Establishment of The Yokohama Rubber Co., Ltd.|url=http://www.y-yokohama.com/global/100th/history/|website=yokohama.com|publisher=Yokohama|accessdate=30 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170331090639/http://www.y-yokohama.com/global/100th/history/|archive-date=31 March 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* The [[United States Oil & Gas Association]] was established in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]] which at the time was considered the \"Oil Capital of the World\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usoga.org/en/about_us/history/|title=A Brief History|publisher=usoga.org|accessdate=May 26, 2014}}</ref>\n* The city of [[South Euclid, Ohio]] was incorporated.<ref>[http://www.cityofsoutheuclid.com/about.htm About South Euclid] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061206004420/http://www.cityofsoutheuclid.com/about.htm |date=2006-12-06 }}, City of South Euclid, Ohio. Retrieved December 29, 2006</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[George Osmond]], American entertainer, patriarch of [[The Osmonds]] family singing group, in [[Etna, Wyoming]] (d. [[2007]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Florence La Badie]], American actress, best known for work in the film serial ''[[The Million Dollar Mystery]]'' in which she performed her own stunts (killed in a car accident) (b. [[1888]])\n\n== [[October 14]], 1917 (Sunday) ==\n* British cargo ship SS ''Semantha'' was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] by German submarine {{SMU|UC-74||6}} with the loss of 32 of her crew.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/wwi/ships_hit/5516.html |title=Semantha |publisher=Uboat.net |accessdate=28 December 2012}}</ref>\n* German submarine {{SMU|UC-62||6}} struck a mine and sank in the [[North Sea]] with the loss of all 26 crew.<ref>{{cite Uboat.net|name=UC 62|id=UC+62 |type=1sub|accessdate=23 February 2009}}</ref>\n* The [[Uruguay national football team]] won its second [[1917 South American Championship|South American Championship]], defeating [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] 1\u20130 in the series final in [[Parque Pereira]], [[Montevideo]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Southamerican Championship 1917|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/17safull.html|website=RSSSF.com|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n* The [[St. Clements Roman Catholic Church (Saratoga Springs, New York)|St. Clements Roman Catholic Church]] held first [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]] in [[Saratoga Springs, New York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stclementschurch.com/our-parish/our-parish/|work=St. Clement's Church|title=The First Mass \u2014 As told from history of St. Clement's Parish|accessdate=December 16, 2012}}</ref>\n* The historic drama ''[[Cleopatra (1917 film)|Cleopatra]]'' was released, with [[Theda Bara]] in the starring role as the Egyptian queen. Directed by [[J. Gordon Edwards]], the film also starred [[Fritz Leiber (actor)|Fritz Leiber]] as [[Julius Caesar]] and [[Thurston Hall]] as [[Mark Antony]]. Controversy around its sensual images only made the film more popular the biggest hit of 1917.<ref>{{cite book|last1=McCaffrey|first1=Donald W.|last2=Jacobs|first2=Christopher P.|title=Guide to the Silent Years of American Cinema|year=1999|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=0-313-30345-2|page=[https://archive.org/details/guidetosilentyea00mcca/page/82 82]|url=https://archive.org/details/guidetosilentyea00mcca/page/82}}</ref> The film was considered lost but some fragments along with production stills survived, allowing a portion of the film to be reconstructed for screening at the [[Hollywood Heritage Museum]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ziemba|first1=Christine N.|title=Twenty Of The Coolest Events Happening in L.A. This Week|url=http://laist.com/2017/02/06/20_of_the_coolest_events_happening_2.php|accessdate=9 March 2017|agency=Laist|date=February 6, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170501083710/http://laist.com/2017/02/06/20_of_the_coolest_events_happening_2.php|archivedate=1 May 2017}}</ref>\n* The Argentine [[association football]] club [[Almirante Brown de Arrecifes]] was established in [[Arrecifes]], [[Argentina]].<ref>[http://www.clarin.com/deportes/Querido_Ascenso_0_278972304.html \"Brown de Arrecifes: un viaje de ida y vuelta\"], Clar\u00edn web, 2010-06-11</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Geoffrey Bibby]], English [[archaeologist]], best known for the discovery of the ancient city of [[Dilmun]] and the pioneer of Arabian archaeology, in [[Heversham]], [[England]] (d. [[2001 in archaeology|2001]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Nathaniel Hone the Younger]], Irish painter, member of the [[Hone family]] (b. [[1831 in art|1831]]); [[Eddie Latheron]], English [[association football]] player, [[inside forward]] for the [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.]] from 1906 to 1917 and the [[England national football team]] from 1913 to 1914 (killed at the [[Battle of Passchendaele]]) (b. [[1887]])\n\n== [[October 15]], 1917 (Monday) ==\n* [[Battle of Mahiwa]] &ndash; Nigerian colonial troops under command of [[General]] [[Jacob van Deventer (general)|Jacob van Deventer]] fought German colonial soldiers under command of [[Major-General]] [[Kurt Wahle]] at [[Mahiwa, Tanzania|Mahiwa]], [[German East Africa]] (now [[Tanzania]]). General [[Paul von Lettow-Vorbeck]], commander of forces in [[German East Africa]], sent additional battalions that encircled the Nigerian force.<ref>{{cite book| last=Paice|first=Edward|title=Tip & Run: The Untold Tragedy of the Great War in Africa| origyear=2007| year=2008| publisher=Phoenix| location=London| isbn=978-0-7538-2349-1|page=330}}</ref>\n* The first [[Action of 15 October 1917|naval action]] between the [[U.S. Navy]] and [[Imperial German Navy]] occurred when American destroyer [[USS Cassin (DD-43)|USS ''Cassin'']] exchanged fire with German submarine [[SM U-61|SM ''U-61'']] off the coast of [[Ireland]], with both vessels damaged. The sole casualty was U.S. sailor [[Osmond Ingram]], who jettisoned several depth charges from a point where a German torpedo was about to hit, saving the ship from catastrophic damage. He was awarded the [[Medal of Honor]] posthumously, and was the first recorded enlisted American casualty of [[World War One]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/photos/pers-us/uspers-i/o-ingram.htm |title=Gunner's Mate First Class Osmond K. Ingram, USN, (1887-1917) |author= |date=20 November 2007 |website= |publisher=Naval Historical Center |accessdate=23 February 2012}}</ref>\n* Dutch dancer [[Mata Hari]] was executed by [[firing squad]] at [[Vincennes]] outside [[Paris]] for [[espionage|spying]] on behalf of [[Germany]].<ref>[http://www.eyewitnesstohistory.com/matahari.htm Execution of Mata Hari]. Eyewitnesstohistory.com (19 October 1917). Retrieved on 2011-10-15.</ref>\n* The [[Chicago White Sox]] defeated the [[New York Giants (NL)|New York Giants]] to win the [[1917 World Series|World Series]] by four games to two.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cohen|first1=Richard M.|last2=Neft|first2=David S.|title=The World Series: Complete Play-By-Play of Every Game, 1903\u20131989|date=1990|publisher=St. Martin's Press.|location=New York|isbn=0-312-03960-3|pages=[https://archive.org/details/worldseries0000cohe/page/66 66\u201370]|url=https://archive.org/details/worldseries0000cohe/page/66}}</ref>\n* [[Royal Navy]] air officer [[John Alcock (RAF officer)|John Alcock]] oversaw the first test flight of his experimental fighter biplane, named the [[Alcock Scout]]. However, only one had been made and when it crashed on another test flight in 1918, no further models were built.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bruce|first=J.M.|title=War Planes of the First World War: Volume One Fighters|year=1965|publisher=Macdonald|location=London|page=8}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Alan W. Livingston]], American music and television producer, best known for the television western ''[[Bonanza]]'' and the creation of [[Bozo the Clown]], founder of [[Capitol Records]], in [[McDonald, Pennsylvania]] (d. [[2009]]); [[Jan Miner]], American actress, best known as Madge in the television [[Colgate-Palmolive]] commercials, in [[Boston]] (d. [[2004]]); [[Arthur M. Schlesinger Jr.]], American historian, recipient for the [[Pulitzer Prize for Biography or Autobiography]] for his historic volume ''[[A Thousand Days]]'' on the [[Presidency of John F. Kennedy]], in [[Columbus, Ohio]] (d. [[2007]])\n* '''Born:''' [[Ruair\u00ed Brugha]], Irish politician, member of the [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] (Irish Parliament) from 1962 to 1982, in [[Dublin]]) (d. [[2006]]); [[Kevin Boland]], Irish politician, cabinet minister for the [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann|Irish Assembly]] from 1965 to 1976, in [[Dublin]] (d. [[2001]]); [[Adele Stimmel Chase]], American artist, best known for her ceramics works that became part of [[Pop art]] and [[Op art]] movements, in [[San Francisco]] (d. [[2000]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Maxime Collignon]], French archaeologist, known for his research in ancient Greek art and architecture (b. [[1849 in archaeology|1849]])\n\n== [[October 16]], 1917 (Tuesday) ==\n* The first [[1917 Dutch East Indies Volksraad election|free elections]] in the [[Dutch East Indies]] were held.<ref>Karel Steenbrink (2007) ''The spectacular growth of a self confident minority, 1903 - 1942'' KITLV Press, p. 44</ref>\n* [[Battle of Moon Sound]] &ndash; British submarines engaged but failed to halt the progress of a German naval squadron dispatched to control the [[Baltic Sea]] around the [[West Estonian archipelago]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Staff|first=Gary|title=Operation Albion| url=http://www.gwpda.org/naval/albion3.htm| accessdate=October 18, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Battle of Mahiwa]] &ndash; South African reinforcements attacked German troops from the opposing side, but the Germans regrouped to a ridge near [[Mahiwa, Tanzania|Mahiwa]] to hold off the attacks.<ref>Paice 2008, p. 330</ref>\n* [[Operation Albion]] &ndash; German forces won complete control of the island of [[Saaremaa]] in the [[Baltic Sea]].{{sfn|Barrett|2008|p=8}} \n* '''Born:''' [[Alice Pearce]], American actress, best known as [[Gladys Kravitz]] in the 1960s television sitcom ''[[Bewitched]]'' in which she won an [[Emmy]] posthumously, in [[New York City]] (d. [[1966]]); [[Murray MacLehose, Baron MacLehose of Beoch|Murray MacLehose]], British colonial administrator, 25th [[Governor of Hong Kong]], in [[Glasgow]] (d. [[2000]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Walter Flex]], German writer, author of ''The Wanderer between the Two Worlds'' (killed in action) (b. [[1887]])\n\n== [[October 17]], 1917 (Wednesday) ==\n* German [[light cruiser]]s {{SMS|Brummer||2}} and {{SMS|Bremse||2}} [[Action off Lerwick|ambushed]] an [[Allies of World War I|Allied]] convoy in the [[North Sea]], sinking British [[destroyer]]s {{HMS|Mary Rose|1915|2}} and {{HMS|Strongbow|1916|2}} along with several Scandinavian merchant ships carrying coal. Over 300 naval and civilian crew were killed in the attack.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=German naval raid. |day_of_week=Monday |date=22 October 1917 |page_number=8 |issue=41615 |column=C-D }}</ref>\n* [[Battle of Moon Sound]] &ndash; German and Russian naval squadrons clashed in the Baltic Sea, ending with a Russian retreat and the loss of its [[pre-dreadnought]] ship ''Slava'', which was too damaged to retreat and had to be scuttled.<ref>Staff 2012</ref>\n* [[U.S. Army]] troopship [[SS Antilles (1907)|USAT ''Antilles'']] was torpedoed and damaged in the [[Bay of Biscay]] by German submarine {{SMU|U-105||6}} with the loss of 67 lives. Survivors were rescued by {{USS|Corsair|SP-159|6}} before the ship was scuttled.<ref>{{cite DANFS | title=Corsair| url=http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/patrol/corsair.htm |accessdate=2 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/wwi/ships_hit/359.html |title=Antilles |publisher=Uboat.net |accessdate=25 October 2012}}</ref>\n* The [[Trans-Australian Railway]] opened, linking 1,052 miles (1,693&nbsp;km) of railroad between [[Port Augusta, South Australia|Port Augusta]] in [[South Australia]] and [[Kalgoorlie]] in [[Western Australia]]. The rail included 309 miles (497&nbsp;km) of straight rail with no curves across the [[Nullarbor Plain]], making it the world's longest railway straight.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Golden Jubilee of the Trans Australian Railway| author=Chambers, T.F. |journal=[[Australian Railway History]] |pages=267\u201375 |date=November 1968}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| last=Burke| first=David| year=1991|title=Road through the Wilderness: the story of the transcontinental railway, the first great work of Australia's federation| location=Kensington|publisher=New South Wales University Press|isbn=0-86840-140-4}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Ferneyhough|first=Frank|title=The History of Railways in Britain|location=Reading|publisher=Osprey|year=1975|isbn=0-85045-060-8}}</ref>\n* The [[Co-operative Party]] was formed as the official political party of the [[British co-operative movement]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=James C. Docherty|author2=Peter Lamb|title=Historical Dictionary of Socialism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JRYjU-L4F7wC&pg=PA90|year=2006|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-6477-1|page=90}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Arthur Birnie|title=An Economic History of the British Isles|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9UL-AQAAQBAJ&pg=PA367|year=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-58979-9|page=367}}</ref>\n* The German [[association football]] club [[BC Aichach]] was established in [[Aichach]], [[Germany]].<ref>[http://www.bc-aichach.de/ Chronik des BC Aichach] {{in lang|de}} BC Aichach website, accessed: 8 November 2011</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Martin Donnelly (cricketer)|Martin Donnelly]], New Zealand cricketer, member of the [[New Zealand national cricket team]] in 1937, in [[Ng\u0101ruaw\u0101hia]], [[New Zealand]] (d. [[1999]]); [[Dick Young (sportswriter)|Dick Young]], American sports journalist, baseball columnist for the ''[[New York Daily News]]'' for 45 years (d. [[1987]])\n* '''Born:''' [[Marsha Hunt (actress, born 1917)|Marsha Hunt]], American actress, known for her roles in ''[[Born to the West]]'', ''[[These Glamour Girls]]'', and ''[[Johnny Got His Gun (film)|Johnny Got His Gun]]'', member of the [[Committee for the First Amendment]] during the Hollywood blacklist, in [[Chicago]]; [[Sumner Locke Elliott]], Australian writer, author of ''[[Careful, He Might Hear You (novel)|Careful, He Might Hear You]]'' and ''[[Rusty Bugles]]'', in [[Sydney]] (d. [[1991]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Bobby Atherton]], Welsh [[association football]] player, midfielder and forward for various clubs including [[Hibernian F.C.]] and [[Middlesbrough F.C.]] from 1897 to 1906, member of the [[Wales national football team]] from 1899 to 1905 (missing in action) (b. [[1876]]); [[John Franklin Botume]], American singer and choir director, author on several books on singing including ''Modern Singing Methods: Their Use and Abuse'' (b. [[1855]])\n\n== [[October 18]], 1917 (Thursday) ==\n* [[Battle of Mahiwa]] &ndash; A German force of 1,500 men counterattacked and repelled the attacking South African and Nigerian force of 4,900 men, inflicting 2,700 casualties. The Germans suffered between 500-600 casualties, or thirty percent of its strength.<ref>Paice 2008, pp. 331-332</ref> \n* [[Operation Albion]] &ndash; Russian forces evacuated from [[Muhu]] in the [[Baltic Sea]].{{sfn|Barrett|2008|p=8}}\n* '''Born:''' [[Robert A. Lewis]], American air force officer, co-pilot of the ''[[Enola Gay]]'' that dropped the first [[A-bomb]] on [[Hiroshima]], in [[Ridgefield Park, New Jersey]] (d. [[1983]])\n\n== [[October 19]], 1917 (Friday) ==\n* [[Operation Albion]] &ndash; German forces landed at [[Hiiumaa]] Island in the [[Baltic Sea]].{{sfn|Barrett|2008|p=8}}\n* [[Battle of Moon Sound]] &ndash; German ships entered the Gulf of Riga and began to clear the minefield, where most casualties occurred during the operation.<ref>Staff 2012</ref>\n* Thirteen Zeppelins set out on a high-altitude raid against the middle of [[England]] but severe weather conditions prevented all but two in reaching their targets. One of the airships bombed [[London]], killing 24 people and injuring nine others, as well destroying the [[Austin Motor Company|Austin Motor Works]] plant at [[Longbridge]], [[England]]. The second airship bombed [[Northampton]] and [[London]], killing 24 people and injuring nine others.<ref>Whitehouse 1966, pp. 223-232, 236, 243</ref>\n* [[Carl Swartz]] left office as [[Prime Minister of Sweden]] after dismal election results for the right-wing party in the September [[Riksdag]] elections. He was replaced by liberal leader [[Nils Ed\u00e9n]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Sweden.html|title=Sweden|publisher=World Statesmen|language=Swedish|accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref>\n* American [[ocean liner]] {{SS|J. L. Luckenbach||2}} was torpedoed and damaged in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] by German submarine {{SMU|U-62||6}}. She was escorted to [[Le Havre]], [[Seine-Maritime]], [[France]] by [[U.S. Navy]] [[destroyer]] {{USS|Nicholson|DD-52|6}} where she was subsequently repaired and returned to service.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Sims | first1 = William Sowden | last2 = Hendrick | first2 = Burton Jesse | authorlink1 = William Sims | authorlink2 = Burton J. Hendrick | title = The Victory at Sea | location = [[Garden City, New York]] | publisher = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday, Page & Co.]] | year = 1920 | oclc = 1058119 | pages = 148\u201349 | title-link = The Victory at Sea }}</ref>\n* [[Dallas Love Field]] was opened in [[Dallas]] as a military base for training pilots enlisted in [[World War One]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.archives.gov/research/guide-fed-records/groups/018.html#18.5.4|title=Records of the Army Air Forces [AAF]| website=Archives.gov| accessdate=June 10, 2016}}</ref>\n* The ''[[Luftstreitkr\u00e4fte]]'', the air arm of the [[Imperial German Army]], established air squadron ''[[Jagdstaffel 80]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theaerodrome.com/services/germany/jasta/jasta80.php |title=Jasta 80 |work=The Aerodrome |year=2015 |accessdate=18 December 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* The [[Institute of Quarrying]] was established during a meeting of quarry managers in [[Caernarfon]], [[Wales]]. The organization expanded with branches in [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], [[Malaysia]], [[South Africa]] and [[Hong Kong]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Institute of Quarrying Timeline| url=http://www.quarrying.org/about-us/iq-timeline|website=Quarrying.org|publisher=Institute of Quarrying|accessdate=8 April 2017}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Walter Munk]], Austrian-American oceanographer, best known for his tidal research into oceans and ocean currents with the [[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]], in [[Vienna]] (d. [[2019]]); [[Evgenia Antipova]], Russian artist, member of the [[Leningrad School of Painting]], in [[Toropets]], [[Russia]] (d. [[2009]]); [[Robert P. Baldwin]], American air force pilot, recipient of the [[Silver Star]] and [[Legion of Merit]] for action during the [[Korean War]], in [[Los Angeles]] (d. [[1994]])\n\n== [[October 20]], 1917 (Saturday) ==\n* [[Operation Albion]] &ndash; German forces occupied all of [[Hiiumaa]] Island in the [[Baltic Sea]], ending the campaign.{{sfn|Barrett|2008|p=8}}\n* British cargo ship ''{{SS|Mahratta|1917|2}}'' was launched by Robert Duncan & Co in [[Port Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]. In a remarkable coincidence, the ship was wrecked in the [[English Channel]] in the exact spot as its predecessor.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.clydesite.co.uk/clydebuilt/viewship.asp?id=17059 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526062555/http://www.clydesite.co.uk/clydebuilt/viewship.asp?id=17059 | url-status=usurped | archive-date=2011-05-26 |title=Launched 1917: ss MAHRATTA |publisher=clydesite |accessdate=2008-11-08}}</ref>\n* Police in [[Washington D.C.]] arrested [[Alice Paul]], a prominent member of the suffragist protest group [[Silent Sentinels]], while she carried a banner that quoted [[U.S. President]] [[Woodrow Wilson]]: \"The time has come to conquer or submit, for us there can be but one choice. We have made it.\" Paul was sentenced to seven months in prison where, after enduring two weeks of solitary confinement, was released to prison hospital where she started a hunger strike to protest the poor conditions of the [[Virginia]] penitentiary where many fellow Sentinel members were also imprisoned.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Stevens|first1=Doris|title=Jailed for Freedom|date=1920|publisher=Liverright Publishing|location=New York, NY}}</ref>\n* Irish poet [[W. B. Yeats]], then 51, married 25-year-old [[Georgie Hyde-Lees]] at the [[Harrow Road]] [[register office]] in [[London]] with [[Ezra Pound]] as best man. It had been a couple of months after he had a proposal of marriage to his ex-mistress's daughter, [[Iseult Gonne]], rejected.<ref>Cahill, Christopher. \"Second Puberty: The Later Years of W. B. Yeats Brought His Best Poetry, along with Personal Melodrama on an Epic Scale\". ''The Atlantic Monthly'', December 2003.</ref> \n* The [[U.S. Army]] established the [[Aberdeen Proving Ground]] in [[Aberdeen, Maryland]] as an ordinance testing site.<ref>{{cite web|title=History of APG|url=http://armyalliance.org/about-apg/history-of-apg/|website=Army Alliance|accessdate=3 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170429091304/http://armyalliance.org/about-apg/history-of-apg/|archive-date=29 April 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Jean-Pierre Melville]], French film director, best known for his [[French New Wave]] crime dramas ''[[Le Doulos]]'', ''[[Le Samoura\u00ef]]'', and ''[[Le Cercle rouge]]'', in [[Paris]] (d. [[1973]]); [[William F. Barnes]], American college football player and coach, served as coach for the [[UCLA Bruins football]] team from 1958 to 1964, in [[Cape Girardeau, Missouri]] (d. [[2009]]); [[St\u00e9phane Hessel]], German-French diplomat and Holocaust survivor, author of ''[[Time for Outrage!]]'', in [[Berlin]] (d. [[2013]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Elise Kemp]], New Zealand nurse, only military nurse from the country to be killed in action in [[World War One]] (b. [[1881]]); [[John T. Wilder]], American army officer, Union commander at the [[Battle of Hoover's Gap]] during the [[American Civil War]] (b. [[1830]])\n\n== [[October 21]], 1917 (Sunday) ==\n* [[Malta]] held a [[1917 Maltese general election|general election]] for six out of its eight seats.<ref>Michael J Schiavone (1987) ''L-Elezzjonijiet F'Malta 1849\u20131981'', Pubblikazzjoni Bugelli, p.19</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Dizzy Gillespie]], American jazz trumpet musician, credited for the development of [[bebop]] and promotion of [[Afro-Cuban music]], in [[Cheraw, South Carolina]] (d. [[1993]])\n\n== [[October 22]], 1917 (Monday) ==\n* British forces launched two [[Action of 22 October 1917|separate assaults]] on the German front in [[Belgium]], capturing the village of [[Langemark-Poelkapelle|Polecappelle]] but failing to seize a key road junction north of [[Houthulst]] Forest from German control.<ref>{{cite book |title=To Play a Giant's Part: The Role of the British Army at Passchendaele |last=Perry |first=R. A. |authorlink= |year=2014 |publisher=Naval & Military Press |location=Uckfield |edition= |isbn=978-1-78331-146-0|pages=470\u2013480}}</ref> British casualties were 479 while German casualties were unknown, save for 125 prisoners.{{sfn|Epdmonds|1991|=348}}\n* U.S. President [[Woodrow Wilson]] appointed [[A. Mitchell Palmer]] to head the [[Office of Alien Property Custodian]] which administered property seized from those deemed an enemy of the [[United States]] during [[World War One]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Coben|first1=Stanley|title=A. Mitchell Palmer: Politician|date=1963|publisher=Columbia University Press|location=New York|pages=128\u2013135}}</ref>\n* The [[Charlie Chaplin]]-directed film ''[[The Adventurer (1917 film)|The Adventurer]]'', starring Chaplin regulars [[Edna Purviance]] and [[Eric Campbell (actor)|Eric Campbell]], was released through [[Mutual Film]]. It was the last film by Campbell before his death in a car accident two months later.<ref>{{cite web|title=Charlie Chaplin's \"The Adventurer\" (1917)|url=https://archive.org/details/CC_1917_10_22_TheAdventurer|via=[[Internet Archive]] |accessdate=19 February 2013}}</ref>\n* The [[Sherlock Holmes]] anthology of previously published stories ''[[His Last Bow (short story)|His Last Bow]]'' included the newest short story of the same name by [[Arthur Conan Doyle]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sshf.com/encyclopedia/index.php/His_Last_Bow |title=His Last Bow |website=De Encyclop\u00e9die de Conan doyle & Sherlock Holmes |publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Sherlock Holmes de France |accessdate=21 January 2014}}</ref>\n* The first section of the [[Seibu Tamagawa Line]] for [[Tokyo]] opened for service.<ref>{{cite book |last = Terada |first = Hirokazu |title = \u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d6\u30c3\u30af\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u79c1\u9244 |trans-title= Databook: Japan's Private Railways |publisher = Neko Publishing |date = 19 January 2013 |location = Japan |page =227 |isbn = 978-4-7770-1336-4}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Joan Fontaine]], British-American actress, known for her roles in ''[[Rebecca (1940 film)|Rebecca]]'', ''[[Jane Eyre (1943 film)|Jane Eyre]]'' and ''[[The Constant Nymph (1943 film)|The Constant Nymph]]'', recipient of the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]] for her role in ''[[Suspicion (1941 film)|Suspicion]]'', sister to [[Olivia de Havilland]], in [[Tokyo]] (d. [[2013]]) \n* '''Died:''' [[Bob Fitzsimmons]], British boxer, held world champion titles in all three major weight classes, considered the lightest heavyweight champion in the ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' (b. [[1863]])\n\n== [[October 23]], 1917 (Tuesday) ==\n* [[Battle of La Malmaison]] &ndash; The [[Sixth Army (France)|French Sixth Army]] attacked the German-held French village and fort of [[La Malmaison]], [[France]], capturing the communes of [[Allemant, Marne|Allemant]] and [[Vaudesson]].<ref>{{cite book| title=The Times History of the War | volume=XVI| year=1914\u20131921| publisher=The Times| location=London| accessdate=29 June 2014| oclc=70406275| pages=234\u2013241| url=https://archive.org/details/timeshistoryofwa16londuoft}}</ref>\n* [[Battle of Wadi Musa]] &ndash; A force of 700 Arab rebel troops ambushed an Ottoman column dispatched to secure the [[Hejaz]] railway in [[Jordan]], killing 400 men and capturing 300 prisoners.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Murphy|first1=David|title=The Arab Revolt 1916\u201318 Lawrence sets Arabia Ablaze|date=2008|publisher=Osprey|location=London|isbn=978-1-84603-339-1|pages=56\u201357}}</ref>\n* [[October Revolution]] &ndash; The [[Bolshevik Party]] voted in favor of overthrowing the [[Russian Provisional Government]], with a resolution citing \"an armed uprising is inevitable, and that the time for it is fully ripe.\"<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.marxists.org/archive/lenin/works/1917/oct/10a.htm| title=Central Committee Meeting\u201410 Oct 1917}}</ref>\n* The Canadian Railway War Board (predecessor of the [[Railway Association of Canada]]) met for the first time at [[Windsor Station (Montreal)|Windsor Station]] in [[Montreal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railways.incanada.net/candate/candate.htm|title=Significant dates in Canadian railway history|work=Colin Churcher's Railway Pages|date=2006-09-15|accessdate=2006-10-23|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061023182151/http://www.railways.incanada.net/candate/candate.htm|archivedate=23 October 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/releases/archive/October2007/23/c7258.html|title=Historic Anniversary for the Railway Association of Canada|date=2007-10-23|accessdate=2007-10-23|publisher=Railway Association of Canada}}</ref>\n* The German government established the Reich Economic Office, the predecessor to the [[Federal Ministry for Economic Affairs and Energy]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The history of the Federal Ministry of Economics and Energy| url=http://www.bmwi.de/Navigation/DE/Ministerium/Geschichte/geschichte.html| website=BMWi| language=German}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Robert Bray]], American actor, best known for the role of ranger [[Corey Stuart]] in the TV series ''[[Lassie (1954 TV series)|Lassie]]'', in [[Kalispell, Montana]] (d. [[1983]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Eug\u00e8ne Grasset]], Swiss artist, pioneer of [[Art Nouveau]] (b. [[1845 in art|1845]])\n\n== [[October 24]], 1917 (Wednesday) ==\n* [[Battle of Caporetto]] &ndash; Also known as the Twelfth Battle of the Isonzo, Austro-Hungarian and German forces triggered 894 canisters that released chlorine gas onto the [[Second Army (Italy)|Italian Second Army]] entrenched in the valley. Most Italian soldiers retreated as their supplied gas masks could only last for two hours, with an estimated 500 to 600 defenders killed.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Stearns |first1=Peter |last2=Langer |first2=William|title=The Encyclopedia of World History |edition=6th |year=2001 |publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt |isbn=0-395-65237-5 |page=669}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Haber |first=Leonard |title=The Poisonous Cloud: Chemical Warfare in the First World War |year=1986 |publisher= Clarendon Press |isbn=0198581424 |page=186}}</ref> The [[Central Powers]] then used [[infiltration tactics]] and [[stormtroopers]] armed with light machine guns, mortar launchers, grenades and flamethrowers to break through the line, leading to its collapse six days later.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gudmundsson|first=Bruce|title=Stormtroop Tactics. Innovation in the German Army, 1914\u20131918|year=1989|publisher=Praeger|isbn=0-275-93328-8|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/briefhistoryofka00kamm}}</ref><ref>Seth, Ronald (1965). ''Caporetto: The Scapegoat Battle''. Macdonald. p. 147</ref> \n* The [[No. 190 Squadron RAF|No. 190 Squadron]] was established by the [[Royal Flying Corps]] at [[Rochford]], [[England]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/190squadron.cfm |title=190 Squadron |website=Royal Air Force |accessdate=8 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304043046/http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/190squadron.cfm |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Australian Flying Corps]] established air squadrons [[No. 7 Squadron RAAF|No. 7]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.airforce.gov.au/raafmuseum/research/units/7sqn.htm |title=No 7 Squadron, Royal Australian Air Force |publisher=RAAF Museum |accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref> and [[No. 8 Squadron RAAF|No. 8]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.airforce.gov.au/raafmuseum/research/units/8sqn.htm |title=No 8 Squadron, Royal Australian Air Force |publisher=RAAF Museum |accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref>\n* Telephone inventor [[Alexander Graham Bell]] attended the unveiling of a [[Bell Memorial|monument]] to him in front of a crowd of thousands in [[Brantford]], [[Ontario]].<ref>{{citation |last=McMeal |first=Harry B. |title=Unveiling of Bell Memorial at Brantford, Ontario, Ca. | publisher=Telephone Pub. Corp. |year=1917 |volume=73 |page=21}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Denys Val Baker]], Welsh writer, author of ''The Door is Always Open'' and ''The Sea\u2019s in The Kitchen'', in [[Upper Poppleton]], [[England]] (d. [[1984]]); [[Donald N. Aldrich]], American marine officer, recipient of the [[Navy Cross]] and [[Air Medal]] for action in the [[Solomon Islands campaign]] during [[World War Two]], in [[Moline, Illinois]] (d. [[1947]], killed in a plane crash)\n* '''Died:''' [[James Carroll Beckwith]], American artist, member of the [[Naturalism (art)|Naturalism]] movement in the [[United States]] (b. [[1852]])\n\n== [[October 25]], 1917 (Thursday) ==\n* The [[Petrograd Military Revolutionary Committee]] was established with [[Leon Trotsky]] as leader to organize the overthrow of the [[Russian Provisional Government]].<ref>{{cite book| last1=Suny| first1=Ronald| title=The Soviet Experiment| date=2011| publisher=Oxford University Press| pages=63\u201367}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Military Revolutionary Committees| url=http://bse.sci-lib.com/article005983.html| website=Great Soviet Encyclopedia|accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref>\n* Some 1,700 [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] delegates attended a convention in the [[Mansion House, Dublin|Dublin Mansion House]] as [[Arthur Griffith]] was replaced as the organisation's president with [[\u00c9amon de Valera]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Packenham|first1=Frank|title=\u00c9amon de Valera|date=1974|publisher=Arrow Books|page=68|url=https://books.google.com/?id=r7MMAQAAMAAJ&q=%22no+contemplation+in+it%22|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref>\n* The French Lyceum was established in [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb]], [[Albania]], later renamed the [[Albanian National Lyceum]] in 1921 and the [[Raqi Qirinxhi High School]] in 1944.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bashkiakorce.gov.al/frontend/article.php?aid=142&cid=51 |title=Liceu Francez i Korces |last=Municipality of Korce web page |language=Albanian |accessdate=3 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100116061312/http://www.bashkiakorce.gov.al/frontend/article.php?aid=142&cid=51 |archivedate=16 January 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Carl Forssell]], Swedish fencer, bronze medalist in the [[1948 Summer Olympics]] and silver medalist in the [[1952 Summer Olympics]], in [[Stockholm]] (d. [[2005]]); [[Lee MacPhail]], American sports executive, president and general manager of the [[Baltimore Orioles]] and [[New York Yankees]], and president of the [[American League]], son to [[Larry MacPhail]], in [[Nashville, Tennessee]] (d. [[2012]]); [[William Remington]], American economist, convicted of perjury stemming from espionage charges made by Soviet spy [[Elizabeth Bentley]], in [[New York City]] (d. [[1954]], murdered in prison) \n* '''Died:''' [[Jack Standing]], English actor, best known for his [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] roles including ''[[The Belle of New York (musical)|The Belle of New York]]'' and ''[[Florodora]]'', and his film roles such as ''[[Hell's Hinges]]'' (b. [[1886]]); [[Maximilian Bayer]], German army officer, founder of [[Scouting and Guiding in Germany|Scouting in Germany]] and the [[27th J\u00e4ger Battalion (Finland)|27th J\u00e4ger Battalion]] for the [[Imperial German Army]] (killed in action) (b. [[1872]])\n\n== [[October 26]], 1917 (Friday) ==\n* [[Brazil]] [[Brazil during World War I|declared war]] against [[Germany]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Brazil Proclaims War On Germany| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1917/10/27/archives/brazil-proclaims-war-on-germany-president-braz-announces.html|accessdate=8 October 2017|work=The New York Times|issue=October 27, 1917|date=October 26, 1917}}</ref>\n* The Italian military disaster at [[Battle of Caporetto|Caporetto]], [[Italy]] lead to the fall of the [[Paolo Boselli]] government.<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1917/10/27/102371170.pdf Italian Cabinet Resigns Office; Beaten on Vote of Confidence Thursday, the Boselli Ministry Retires], The New York Times, October 27, 1917</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Passchendaele]] &ndash; British and Canadian forces attacked defensive ridges east of the village of [[Passendale|Passchendaele]], [[Belgium]] that the [[Allies of World War I|Allies]] failed to take earlier in the month.<ref>{{cite book| series=Official History of the Canadian Army in the First World War |title=Canadian Expeditionary Force 1914\u20131919 |last=Nicholson |first=G. W. L. |authorlink = G. W. L. Nicholson |year=1962 |publisher=Queen's Printer and Controller of Stationery |location=Ottawa |url=http://www.cmp-cpm.forces.gc.ca/dhh-dhp/his/docs/CEF_e.pdf |accessdate=23 March 2014 |oclc=59609928|pages=318\u2013320}}</ref>\n* The [[U.S. Army]] established the [[2nd Infantry Division (United States)|2nd Infantry Division]] which included the [[3rd Infantry Brigade, 2nd Infantry Division|3rd Infantry Brigade]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/forcestruc/cbtchron/cc/002id.htm|title=Lineage and Honors Information: 2nd Infantry Division |publisher=[[United States Army Center of Military History]] |accessdate=3 November 2009}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Mario Biaggi]], American politician, [[U.S. Representative]] from [[New York (state)|New York]] from 1969 to 1988, in [[New York City]] (d. [[2015]])\n\n== [[October 27]], 1917 (Saturday) ==\n* [[Battle of La Malmaison]] &ndash; The [[Sixth Army (France)|French Sixth Army]] captured the [[Pinon, Aisne|Pinon]] commune and the surrounding forest from the Germans in northern [[France]], thus liberating the village and fort of [[La Malmaison]], [[France]] from German control.{{sfn|Times|1918|pp=245-246}} French losses were 2,241 killed, 8,162 wounded and 1,460 missing. However, French forces captured 11,157 German prisoners and 1,100 machine gun, artillery and mortar pieces.<ref>{{cite book|last=Doughty |first=R. A. |title=Pyrrhic victory: French Strategy and Operations in the Great War |location=Cambridge, MA |publisher=The Belknap Press of Harvard University |year=2005 |isbn=978-0-674-01880-8|pages=384\u2013389}}</ref> German losses were estimated at 38,000 killed or missing.<ref>{{cite book |title=Attriotin: Fighting the First World War |last=Philpott |first=W. |authorlink= |year=2014 |publisher=Little, Brown |location=London |edition= |isbn=978-1-4087-0355-7|page=279}}</ref>\n* [[Third Battle of Gaza]] &ndash; British and French naval vessels bombarded [[Gaza City|Gaza]] to soften Ottoman defensive prior to infantry assault on November 1. An Ottoman aircraft strafed one of the British ships, killing 38 sailors.<ref>{{cite book |title=Military Operations: Egypt & Palestine from June 1917 to the End of the War |last=Falls |first=Cyril |series=Official History of the Great War Based on Official Documents by Direction of the Historical Section of the Committee of Imperial Defence |others=A. F. Becke (maps) |year=1930 |volume=Volume 2 Part I |publisher=HM Stationery Office |location=London|oclc=644354483|pages=65\u201366}}</ref> \n* [[Battle of Buqqar Ridge]] &ndash; The [[Desert Mounted Corps]] repelled an [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] attack on its garrison at el Buqqar Ridge, [[Syria]] during the last days of the [[Stalemate in Southern Palestine]].<ref>Falls 1930, p.37</ref>\n* British flying ace [[Arthur Rhys-Davids]] disappeared while pursuing a German squadron east of [[Roeselare]], [[Belgium]]. His death wasn't confirmed until December 29 when German command informed he had been shot down by German flying ace [[Karl Gallwitz]]. At the time, he had been credited with 27 victories including German aces [[Carl Menckhoff]] and [[Werner Voss]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Revell|first1=Alex|title=Brief Glory: The Life of Arthur Rhys Davids, DSO, MC and Bar'|date=2010|publisher=Pen & Sword Aviation|location=Barnsley|isbn=978-1-84884-162-8|page=200}}</ref>\n* The [[Irish Volunteers]] held its convention immediately following the Sinn F\u00e9in convention, with most of the delegates having attended both. Newly-elected Sinn F\u00e9in president \u00c9amon de Valera was also elected president of the Volunteers.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Valiulis |first1=Maryann |title=Portrait of a Revolutionary: General Richard Mulcahy and the Founding of the Irish Free State |date=1992 |publisher=University Press of Kentucky |isbn=0-8131-1791-7 |page=24 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YGizfkDzVXEC&pg=PA24 |accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Oliver Tambo]], South African politician, President of the [[African National Congress]] from 1967 to 1991, in [[Nkantolo]], [[South Africa]] (d. [[1993]])\n\n== [[October 28]], 1917 (Sunday) ==\n* [[Switzerland]] held its [[1917 Swiss federal election|federal election]], with the [[Free Democratic Party of Switzerland]] retaining its majority in the [[National Council (Switzerland)|National Council]].<ref>[http://www.bfs.admin.ch/bfs/portal/fr/index/themen/17/22/lexi.Document.137139.xls Elections to the National Council 1848\u20131917: Distribution of seats by party or political orientation] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923230855/http://www.bfs.admin.ch/bfs/portal/fr/index/themen/17/22/lexi.Document.137139.xls |date=2015-09-23 }} BFS</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Passchendaele]] &ndash; The Canadian forces advance slowed due to German resistance but were able to hold the line for reinforcements, at a cost of 2,481 casualties.<ref>{{cite book|title=In Flanders Fields, Passchendaele 1917 |last=Wolff |first=L. |year=1979 |orig-year=1958 |publisher=Penguin |edition=reprint |location=London |isbn=978-0-14-004896-4|pages=247\u2013248}}</ref>\n* [[U.S. Army]] troopship {{USAT|Finland}} was torpedoed and damaged in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] off [[Brest, France]] by German submarine {{SMU|U-93||6}} with the loss of nine of her crew.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/wwi/ships_hit/2179/.html |title=Finland |publisher=Uboat.net |accessdate=23 October 2012 }}{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] beat [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] 5-4 and 4\u20132 in the [[1917 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship Final|All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship Final]] in [[Croke Park]], [[Dublin]].<ref>Corry, Eoghan, ''The GAA Book of Lists'' (Hodder Headline Ireland, 2005)</ref><ref>Donegan, Des, ''The Complete Handbook of Gaelic Games'' (DBA Publications Limited, 2005)</ref>\n* The historical romance ''[[The Woman God Forgot]]'', directed by [[Cecil B. DeMille]] and starring [[Geraldine Farrar]] in the title role, was released and became the fifth box office hit of the year. A copy of the film is in the [[George Eastman House Motion Picture Collection]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/W/WomanGodForgot1917.html |title=Progressive Silent Film List: ''The Woman God Forgot'' | accessdate=February 3, 2010|work=Silent Era}}</ref> \n* '''Born:''' [[Jack Soo]], American actor, best known for the role of Nick Yemana in the police television sitcom ''[[Barney Miller]]'', in [[Oakland, California]] (d. [[1979]]); [[Honor Frost]], Cyprus archaeologist, pioneer in [[underwater archaeology]], in [[Nicosia]], [[Cyprus]] (d. [[2010 in archaeology|2010]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Prince Christian of Schleswig-Holstein]], Danish-British noble, husband to [[Princess Helena of the United Kingdom]] (b. [[1831]]); [[Eugenio Elia Levi]], Italian mathematician, known for his contributions to [[group theory]], brother to [[Beppo Levi]] (killed in action) (b. [[1883]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Cecil Rawling]], British explorer, commander of expeditions to [[Tibet]] and [[Dutch New Guinea]] (killed during the [[Battle of Passchendaele]]) (b. [[1870]]); [[Isaac S. Taylor]], American architect, best known for his designs for key buildings in [[St. Louis]] (b. [[1850]])\n\n== [[October 29]], 1917 (Monday) ==\n* [[Battle of Pozzuolo]] &ndash; Two Italian brigades staged a rearguard action against the advancing German and Austrian forces at [[Pozzuolo del Friuli]], [[Italy]] as the [[Second Army (Italy)|Italian Second Army]] retreated from their disastrous defeat at the [[Battle of Caporetto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.difesa.it/Operazioni+Militari/operazioni+in+atto/Kosovo+-+JOINT+GUARDIAN/notizie-teatro-dettaglio.htm?solotesto=true&DetailID=2345|title=Sito del Ministero della Difesa, url consultato il 1/3/2009}}</ref>\n* Three German ''[[Luftstreitkr\u00e4fte]]'' (German Air Force) bombers set out for the first [[heavier-than-air]] night raid on [[England]] in four weeks. Two of the bombers diverted to [[Calais]], [[France]] due to bad weather, but the third reached [[England]] and bombed the [[Essex]] coast.<ref>Fredette 1976, pp. 162-166.</ref>\n* The [[U.S. Army]] established the [[92nd Infantry Division (United States)|92nd Infantry Division]].<ref>{{cite web|title=92nd Infantry Division| url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/forcestruc/cbtchron/cc/092id.htm|publisher=U.S. Army Center of Military History|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref>\n* The [[Merriwa railway line]] in [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]] was completed.<ref>'''''A Short History of the Muswellbrook - Merriwa Branch Line''''' Preston, R.G. [[Australian Railway History|Australian Railway Historical Society Bulletin]], October, 1967 pp. 205-214.</ref>\n* [[Roscoe Arbuckle|Roscoe \"Fatty\" Arbuckle]] and [[Buster Keaton]] starred in the film comedy ''[[Coney Island (1917 film)|Coney Island]]''.<ref>{{cite book| last=Knopf|first=Robert|title=The theater and cinema of Buster Keaton|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fU5qDx7tawIC&pg=PA180|accessdate=21 October 2010|date=August 2, 1999|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-00442-6|page=180}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Eddie Constantine]], American actor, best known for the role of [[Lemmy Caution]], most notably in the [[French New Wave]] science fiction film ''[[Alphaville (film)|Alphaville]]'', in [[Los Angeles]] (d. [[1993]]); [[Harold Garfinkel]], American sociologist, developed [[ethnomethodology]] as a field of inquiry for social behavior, in [[Newark, New Jersey]] (d. [[2011]])\n\n== [[October 30]], 1917 (Tuesday) ==\n* [[Vittorio Emanuele Orlando]] replaced [[Paolo Boselli]] as [[Prime Minister of Italy]] and continued in that role through the rest of the war.<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1917/10/31/102373098.pdf Invasion Cements Italian Unity; All Factions in Accord in Supporting a Vigorous Fighting Policy. Orlando Is Now Premier], The New York Times, October 31, 1917</ref>\n* [[Battle of Caporetto]] &ndash; After delaying a decision for five days despite pressure from his officers, Italian General [[Luigi Cadorna]] relented and ordered the [[Second Army (Italy)|Italian Second Army]] to retreat back to the [[Tagliamento]] River.<ref>Stearns & Langer 2001, p. 669</ref> Meanwhile, the two Italian brigades assigned to protect the rear were destroyed by the German and Austrian forces at the [[Battle of Pozzuolo]].<ref>Ministero della Difesa 2009</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Passchendaele]] &ndash; Canadian forces advanced {{convert|600|yd|m|abbr=on}} from the starting line, capturing key defense positions around the hamlets of Meetcheele and Goudberg, [[Belgium]] at the cost of {{nowrap|2,321 casualties}}.{{sfn|Nicholson|1962|pp=322\u2013323}}\n* [[Charles Stewart (1868\u20131946)|Charles Stewart]] became [[Premier of Alberta]], replacing [[Arthur Sifton]] who had been chosen to be the provincial representative of the federal [[Unionist Party (Canada)|Unionist coalition]] in [[Ottawa]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Lewis Gwynne |last=Thomas |title=The Liberal Party in Alberta |url=https://archive.org/details/liberalpartyinal0000thom |url-access=registration |year=1959 |publisher=University of Toronto Press |location=[[Toronto]], Ontario}}</ref>\n* Twenty-two German [[Gotha]] bombers set out to raid [[London]], with the newly developed 4.5-kg (9.9-lb) [[incendiary bomb]] included in their bomb loads. Fewer than half the bombers reached the London area, and many of the incendiary bombs failed to ignite for the bomb drops that were delivered. The remaining planes bombed [[Kent]], destroying a [[Gas holder|gasometer]] in [[Ramsgate]] but achieving little else. Five of the bombers crashed while attempting to land upon returning to their bases. Bad weather prevented further raids against England until December.<ref>Fredette 1976, pp. 162-166</ref>\n* German [[flying ace]] [[Lieutenant]] [[Heinrich Gontermann]] was performing aerobatics when the upper wing of his [[Fokker Dr.I]] fighter broke off, causing him to crash where he died from injuries. He had 39 victories, tying him with [[Lieutenant]] [[Carl Menckhoff]] as the 13th-highest-scoring German ace of [[World War One]].<ref>Franks, Norman, ''Aircraft Versus Aircraft: The Illustrated Story of Fighter Pilot Combat From 1914 to the Present Day'', London: Grub Street, 1998, {{ISBN|1-902304-04-7}}, p. 63.</ref>\n* The [[\u00c9cole sup\u00e9rieure d'optique|Institut d'optique Graduate School]] was established as a post-secondary school for the field of optics in [[France]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Creation|url=https://www.institutoptique.fr/Institut/Presentation/Histoire/L-histoire-de-l-Institut-d-Optique-la-creation|website=\u00c9cole sup\u00e9rieure d'optique|accessdate=9 April 2017|language=French}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Maurice Trintignant]], French race car driver, member of the [[Formula One]] circuit from 1950 to 1964, winner of the [[1954 24 Hours of Le Mans]] race, in [[Sainte-C\u00e9cile-les-Vignes]], [[France]] (d. [[2005]]); [[Anna Marly]], Russian-French singer and songwriter, known for protest and political songs including \"[[Chant des Partisans]]\" and \"La complainte du partisan\", in [[Saint Petersburg]] (d. [[2006]]) \n* '''Born:''' [[Bobby Bragan]], American baseball player, catcher and shortstop for the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] and [[History of the Brooklyn Dodgers|Brooklyn Dodgers]] from 1940 and 1948, in [[Birmingham, Alabama]] (b. [[2010]]); [[Robert Maheu]], American business executive, CEO of [[Nevada]] operations for [[Howard Hughes]], author of ''Next to Hughes: Behind the Power and Tragic Downfall of Howard Hughes by His Closest Advisor'', in [[Waterville, Maine]] (d. [[2008]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Alex Decoteau]], Canadian-Cree athlete and law enforcer, first indigenous police officer in [[Canada]], track and field representative for [[Canada]] at the [[1912 Summer Olympics]] (killed at the [[Second Battle of Passchendaele]]) (b. [[1887]])\n\n== [[October 31]], 1917 (Wednesday) ==\n* [[Battle of Beersheba (1917)|Battle of Beersheba]] &ndash; The British [[XX Corps (United Kingdom)|XX Corps]] and [[Desert Mounted Corps]] of the [[Egyptian Expeditionary Force]] attacked and captured [[Beersheba]], [[Syria]], from Ottoman forces, ending the [[stalemate in Southern Palestine]] and starting the [[Southern Palestine Offensive]]. Some 1,947 Ottoman troops were taken prisoner and another estimated 1,000 were killed or wounded. British casualties were 171 killed.<ref>{{cite book|last=Grainger|first=John D.|year=2006|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3SVvryoR2A0C|title=The Battle for Palestine, 1917|location=Woodbridge|publisher=Boydell Press|isbn=978-1-843-83263-8|oclc=255698307|page=121}}</ref> The capture of [[Beersheba]] was clinched with a rare (by this date) mounted [[Charge (warfare)|charge]] by the [[Australian Mounted Division]].<ref>12th Light Horse Regiment War Diary October 1917 AWM4-10-17-9</ref><ref>4th Light Horse Regiment War Diary October 1917 AWM4-10-9-34</ref> \n* Real estate services company [[Cushman & Wakefield]] was established in [[New York City]] by brothers-in-law J. Clydesdale Cushman and Bernard Wakefield. The firm now operates in 60 countries and employs more than 43,000 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/books/politics-and-business-magazines/cushman-wakefield-inc|title=Cushman & Wakefield |publisher=Encyclopedia.com |date=2006 |accessdate=2017-02-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/houston/print-edition/2015/05/15/acquisition-next-step-in-cushman-wakefield-s.html |title=Acquisition next step in Cushman & Wakefield's storied history|publisher=Houston Business Journal |date=2015-05-15 |accessdate=2015-02-07}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Patience Gray]], British writer, known for best-selling cook and travel books including ''Plats Du Jour'' and ''Honey From A Weed'', in [[Shackleford]], [[England]] (d. [[2005]]); [[Bruce Bennett (politician)|Bruce Bennett]], American politician, [[Attorney General]] of [[Arkansas]] from 1957 to 1960, in [[Helena, Arkansas]] (d. [[1979]])\n* '''Born:''' [[Evan Mackie]], New Zealand air force officer, commander of the [[No. 92 Squadron RAF|No. 92]] and [[No. 80 Squadron RAF|No. 80 Squadron]] during [[World War Two]], recipient of the [[Distinguished Service Order]] and two [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Crosses]] from both the [[United Kingdom]] and [[United States]], in [[Waihi]], [[New Zealand]] (d. [[1986]]); [[Gordon Steege]], Australian air force officer, held various commands during [[World War Two]] including [[No. 3 Squadron RAAF|No. 3 Squadron]], recipient of the [[Distinguished Service Order]] and the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]], in [[Chatswood, New South Wales]], [[Australia]] (d. [[2013]])\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Events by month links}}\n\n[[Category:October|1917]]\n[[Category:1917|*1917-10]]\n[[Category:Months in the 1910s|*1917-10]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Month in 1917}}\n{{Events by month|1917}}\n{{calendar|year=1917|month=October}}\n\nThe following events occurred in '''October 1917''':\n\n== [[October 1]], 1917 (Monday) ==\n* [[Germany]] launched [[Actions of 30 September \u2013 4 October 1917|counterattacks]] on British positions in [[Polygon Wood]], [[West Flanders]], [[Belgium]].<ref>{{cite book |title=The 23rd Division 1914\u20131919 |last=Sandilands |first=H. R. |authorlink= |year=2003 |orig-year=1925 |publisher=Wm. Blackwood |location=Edinburgh |edition=Naval & Military Press |isbn=978-1-84342-641-7|pages=200\u2013204}}</ref>\n* Eighteen Gotha bombers of the ''[[Luftstreitkr\u00e4fte]]'' (German Air Force) set out on to raid the [[United Kingdom]], with 11 of them reaching [[England]]. British [[antiaircraft gun]]s fired 14,000 rounds at them without scoring a single hit, but falling fragments from spent antiaircraft shells from the worn-out guns killed eight and injured another 67 people.<ref>Fredette, Raymond H., ''The Sky on Fire: The First Battle of Britain 1917\u20131918'', New York: Harvest, 1976, {{ISBN|0-15-682750-6}}, pp. 135, 146-147, 264.</ref>\n* [[U.S. Coast Guard]] ship [[USRC Mohawk (1904)|USS ''Mohawk'']] collided with a British cargo ship in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] off [[Sandy Hook, New Jersey]] and sank, with all 77 crew members rescued.<ref>{{cite book|last=Johnson|first=Robert Irwin|title=Guardians of the Sea, History of the United States Coast Guard, 1915 to the Present|year=1987|publisher=Naval Institute Press, Annapolis, Maryland|isbn=978-0-87021-720-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/guardiansofseahi00john/page/47 47]|url=https://archive.org/details/guardiansofseahi00john/page/47}}</ref>\n* The [[Royal Navy]] conducted the first launch of an aircraft from a [[battleship]]. [[Royal Naval Air Service]] [[Flight Commander]] [[Frederick Rutland]] took off in a [[Sopwith Pup]] fighter from a platform mounted on a 15-inch (381-mm) gun turret of the battlecruiser {{HMS|Repulse|1916|6}}.<ref>Thetford, Owen, ''British Naval Aircraft Since 1912'', Sixth Edition, Annapolis, Maryland: Naval Institute Press, 1991, {{ISBN|1-55750-076-2}}, p. 14.</ref>\n* The [[Royal Navy]] tested an [[aircraft catapult]] for the first time, using a [[compressed air|compressed-air]] catapult aboard [[HMS Slinger (1917)|''Slinger'']] to launch an unmanned [[Short 184]] aircraft in a series of trial launches.<ref>Layman, R.D., ''Before the Aircraft Carrier: The Development of Aviation Vessels 1849-1922'', Annapolis, Maryland: Naval Institute Press, 1989, {{ISBN|0-87021-210-9}}, p. 78.</ref>\n* The [[139th Infantry Regiment (United States)|139th Infantry Regiment]] of the [[U.S. Army]] was established with the merger of infantry regiments from [[Kansas]] and [[Missouri]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kenamore|first1=Clair|title=The story of the 139th infantry|url=https://archive.org/stream/storyof139thinfa00kena/storyof139thinfa00kena_djvu.txt|website=Archive.org|accessdate=3 April 2017}}</ref>\n* The [[U.S. Government]] established the [[Aircraft Board]] with [[Howard E. Coffin]] as chair.<ref>{{cite web| last =Mooney| first =Charles C. and Layman, Martha E.| year =1944| url =http://www.afhra.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-090602-051.pdf| title =Organization of Military Aeronautics, 1907-1935 (Congressional and War Department Action)| work =Air Force Historical Study No. 25| publisher =AFHRA (USAF)| accessdate =14 Dec 2010| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20101227081644/http://www.afhra.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-090602-051.pdf| archivedate =2010-12-27}}, pp. 27-29. 40 ''Stat.'' 296.</ref>\n* [[Albert Einstein]] was appointed director of the newly formed [[Kaiser Wilhelm Society|Kaiser Wilhelm Institute for Physics]] in [[Munich]] (now the [[Max Planck Institute for Physics]]).<ref>\"[https://www.mpp.mpg.de/institut/Geschichte/01_Ubersicht/index.html Geschichte] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150624040347/https://www.mpp.mpg.de/institut/Geschichte/01_Ubersicht/index.html |date=2015-06-24 }}\" (in German). Max Planck Institute for Physics. Abbreviated version in English: \"[https://www.mpp.mpg.de/english/institute/instGeschichte/Overview/index.html History] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150624042614/https://www.mpp.mpg.de/english/institute/instGeschichte/Overview/index.html |date=2015-06-24 }}.\" Retrieved 2015-08-30</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Guido Fibbia]], Italian air force officer, top fighter ace for ''[[Regia Aeronautica]]'' during [[World War Two]], two-time recipient of the [[Silver Medal of Military Valor]] and the [[Iron Cross]], in [[Treviso]], [[Italy]] (d. [[1988]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Ivan Agu\u00e9li]], Swedish artist and writer, known for his melding of [[post-impressionism]] with [[Arabic]] art following his conversion to [[Islam]] (killed in a train accident) (b. [[1869]])\n\n== [[October 2]], 1917 (Tuesday) ==\n* [[Finland]] held [[1917 Finnish parliamentary election|parliamentary elections]] with the [[Social Democratic Party of Finland]] winning 44 per cent of the vote.<ref>Thomas T Mackie & Richard Rose (1991) ''The International Almanac of Electoral History'', Macmillan, p. 243</ref>\n* [[Royal Navy]] [[armoured cruiser]] [[HMS Drake (1901)|HMS ''Drake'']] was torpedoed and sunk by German submarine {{SMU|U-79||2}} off [[Rathlin Island]] with the loss of 18 out of her 900 crew.<ref>{{cite Uboat.net|id=1713|name=HMS Drake|type=1ship|accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref>\n* The Flying Field at Anacostia, a U.S. military air base, was opened to train pilots and test new aircraft. It was renamed the Anacostia Experimental Flying Field shortly thereafter and eventually the [[Bolling Air Force Base]] after [[Colonel]] [[Raynal Bolling]] on July 1, 1918.<ref>[http://www.cnic.navy.mil/JBAB/index.htm CNIC Joint Base Anacostia-Bolling]</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Christian de Duve]], English biologist, recipient of the [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]] for his research into cell biology, in [[Thames Ditton]], [[England]] (d. [[2013]]); [[Cahal Daly]], Irish clergy, [[Archbishop of Armagh]] and [[Primacy of Ireland]] from 1990 to 1996, in [[Loughguile]], [[Ireland]] (d. [[2009]])\n* '''Born:''' [[Charles Drake (actor)|Charles Drake]], American actor, known for roles in ''[[Winchester '73]]'' and ''[[Harvey (film)|Harvey]]'', in [[New York City]] (d. [[1994]]); [[Francis Jackson (composer)|Francis Jackson]], English composer and organist, director of [[York Minster]] from 1946 to 1982, in [[Malton, North Yorkshire]], [[England]]; [[Rosaleen Norton]], New Zealand-Australian occultist, proponent of [[witchcraft]] and [[wiccanism]] in [[Sydney]], earning her the media nickname \"The Witch of Kings Cross\", in [[Dunedin]], [[New Zealand]] (d. [[1979]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Camille Tissot]], French naval officer, pioneer of [[wireless telegraphy]] (b. [[1868]])\n\n== [[October 3]], 1917 (Wednesday) ==\n* A [[Dubno Garrison Revolt|soldiers' revolt]] erupted at a garrison in [[Dubno]], [[Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web|title=1917 Dubno Garrison Revolt|url=http://leksika.com.ua/10360710/ure/dubenskogo_garnizonu_povstannya_1917|website=Ukrainian Soviet Encyclopedia|accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref>\n* German submarine {{SMU|UC-14||6}} struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and sank in the [[North Sea]] with the loss of all 14 crew.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://uboat.net/wwi/boats/index.html?boat=UC+14 |title=UC 14 |publisher=Uboat.net |accessdate=21 November 2012}}</ref>\n* The [[National Party (United States)|National Party of the United States]] held its first conference in [[Chicago]] where it formally endorsed American participation in [[World War One]].<ref>''Platform, Spirit and Aims of the National Party: Founded October 4th, 1917.'' Chicago: The National Party, 1917; pp. 11-12</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Les Schwab]], American business leader, founder of [[Les Schwab Tire Centers]], in [[Bend, Oregon]] (d. [[2007]]); [[Odd Lundberg]], Norwegian speed skater, silver and bronze medalist at the [[1948 Winter Olympics]], in [[Brandbu]], [[Norway]] (d. [[1983]])\n\n== [[October 4]], 1917 (Thursday) ==\n* [[Battle of Broodseinde]] &ndash; The [[British Second Army|British Second]] and [[British Fifth Army|Fifth Armies]], supported by the [[I ANZAC Corps]], overwhelmed [[4th Army (German Empire)|German 4th Army]]'s defenses at Broodseinde Ridge in [[West Flanders]], [[Belgium]]. Some 5,000 German troops were taken prisoner, adding to the 30,000 casualties the army suffered overall in the first 10 days of fighting in October. British suffered around 20,000 casualties, including 6,423 for [[Australia]] and 1,853 for [[New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite book |title=The Third Ypres: Passchendaele, the Day-By-Day Account |last=McCarthy |first=C. |authorlink= |year=1995 |publisher=Arms & Armour Press| location=London| edition=| isbn=978-1-85409-217-5| pages=97\u2013103}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |series=[[Official History of Australia in the War of 1914\u20131918]] |volume=IV |title=The Australian Imperial Force in France, 1917 |last=Bean |first=C. E. W. |authorlink=Charles Bean |year=1941 |orig-year=1933 |publisher=[[Australian War Memorial]] | location=Canberra |edition=online |url=https://www.awm.gov.au/collection/RCDIG1069753/ |accessdate=27 September 2014 |isbn=978-0-7022-1710-4|pages=847\u2013863}}</ref>\n* An Italian royal decree was issued allowing heavy criminal sanctions against anyone who committed or incited acts of defeatism.<ref>{{in lang|it}} [http://storia.camera.it/cronologia/leg-regno-XXIV#nav XXIV Legislatura del Regno d'Italia dal 27 novembre 1913 al 29 settembre 1919], Camera dei deputati, Portale storico (retrieved 29 May 2016)</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Violeta Parra]], Chilean folk musician, leading figure in the [[Nueva canci\u00f3n]] movement that popularized traditional Chilean music, in [[San Carlos, Chile]] (d. [[1967]]); [[Luis Carniglia]], Argentine [[association football]] player and manager, [[striker (association football)|striker]] for the [[Boca Juniors]] in the 1940s and manager for [[Real Madrid C.F.]] in the 1950s, in [[Olivos, Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]] (d. [[2001]]) \n* '''Died:''' [[Dave Gallaher]], Irish-New Zealand rugby player, team captain for [[The Original All Blacks]] and member of the [[New Zealand national rugby union team]] from 1896 to 1909 (killed in action during the [[Battle of Passchendaele]]) (b. [[1873]])\n\n== [[October 5]], 1917 (Friday) ==\n* German submarine {{SMU|UB-41||6}} struck a mine and sank in the [[North Sea]] off with the loss of all 22 crew.<ref>{{cite book| last1=Gr\u00f6ner| first1=Erich|last2=Jung|first2=Dieter| last3=Maass| first3=Martin| translator-last1=Thomas| translator-first1=Keith| translator-last2=Magowan| translator-first2=Rachel| year=1991| title=U-boats and Mine Warfare Vessels| volume=2| work=German Warships 1815\u20131945| location=London| publisher=Conway Maritime Press|isbn=0-85177-593-4|ref=CITEREFGr.C3.B6ner1991}}</ref>\n* The [[Palestine Brigade RAF|Palestine Brigade]] of the [[Royal Flying Corps]] was established to provide air support during the [[Sinai and Palestine Campaign]], which included the [[No. 40 Wing RAF|No. 40 Wing]].<ref>[http://www.rafweb.org/Wings1.htm Wing Nos 1\u201350] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080726013531/http://www.rafweb.org/Wings1.htm |date=2008-07-26 }} at [http://www.rafweb.org/Index.htm Air of Authority \u2014 A History of RAF Organisation]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071226223020/http://www.rafweb.org/Index.htm |date=26 December 2007 }}. Retrieved on 28 February 2009.</ref>\n* British politician [[Arthur Lee, 1st Viscount Lee of Fareham|Arthur Lee]] donated the country house [[Chequers]] to the British government.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chilternsaonb.org/explore-enjoy/interactive-map.html#1331|title=People and history: Chequers|publisher=Chilterns Conservation Board|accessdate=24 January 2012}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Allen Ludden]], American game show host, best known for the television game show ''[[Password (game show)|Password]]'', in [[Mineral Point, Wisconsin]] (d. [[1981]]); [[Magda Szab\u00f3]], Hungarian novelist, known for works including ''Abig\u00e9l'', in [[Debrecen]], [[Hungary]] (d. [[2007]])\n\n== [[October 6]], 1917 (Saturday) ==\n* The fourth and final [[State Duma (Russian Empire)|Duma]], the legislative assembly of the [[Russian Empire]], formally ended and was dissolved, with the [[Russian Provisional Government]] anticipating elections for the [[Russian Constituent Assembly]] to replace it.\n* The [[U.S. Government]] enacted the [[Trading with the Enemy Act of 1917|Trading with the Enemy Act]], which restricted trade with countries hostile to the [[United States]].<ref>[http://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/html/uscode12/usc_sec_12_00000095---a000-notes.html Cornell Law School]</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Marjorie Guthrie]], American choreographer, wife to folk singer [[Woody Guthrie]] and mother to [[Arlo Guthrie]], in [[Atlantic City, New Jersey]] (d. [[1983]]); [[Fannie Lou Hamer]], American activist, chief organizer of [[Freedom Summer]] for the civil rights movement, in [[Montgomery County, Mississippi]] (d. [[1977]])\n\n== [[October 7]], 1917 (Sunday) ==\n* The largest airship ever built at the time, the ''L 57'', was wrecked and destroyed by fire while trying to take off for a test flight in poor weather. The [[Zeppelin]] aircraft was 743 feet (226.5 meters) in length and could carry 2,418,700 [[cubic foot|cubic feet]] (68,490 [[cubic meters]]) of [[hydrogen gas]] for long distance flights from [[Europe]] to [[Africa]].<ref>Whitehouse, Arch, ''The Zeppelin Fighters'', New York: Ace Books, 1966, no ISBN number, p. 234.</ref>\n* German submarine {{SMU|U-106||6}} struck a mine and sank in the [[North Sea]] with the loss of all 41 crew.<ref>{{cite Uboat.net|id=106|name=U 106|type=1sub|accessdate=25 January 2010}}</ref> \n* '''Born:''' [[June Allyson]], American actress, best known for her on-screen pairings with [[Van Johnson]] in films such as ''[[Too Young to Kiss]]'' in which she won a [[Golden Globe]], in [[New York City]] (d. [[2006]]); [[Rose Piper]], American painter, known for abstract works inspired by [[blues]] music including ''The Death of Bessie Smith'', in [[New York City]] (d. [[2005]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Serhii Vasylkivsky]], Ukrainian artist, known his prolific work on the Ukraine including the ''Cossack'' series (b. [[1854]])\n\n== [[October 8]], 1917 (Monday) ==\n* German submarine {{SMU|U-96||6}} sank British cargo ships SS ''Memphian'' and SS ''Greldon'' in [[St. George's Channel]], killing 32 and 28 crew respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/wwi/ships_hit/4073.html |title=Memphian |publisher=Uboat.net |accessdate=24 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/wwi/ships_hit/2610.html |title=Greldon |publisher=Uboat.net |accessdate=24 October 2012}}</ref>\n* German submarine {{SMU|U-57||6}} sank British cargo ship SS ''Richard de Larrinaga'' in the [[Atlantic Ocean]], killing 35 crew.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/wwi/ships_hit/5113.html |title=Richard De Larrinaga |publisher=Uboat.net |accessdate=12 October 2012}}</ref> \n* The [[Royal Flying Corps]] established air squadrons [[No. 90 Squadron RAF|No. 90]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/90squadron.cfm |title=90 Squadron |website=Royal Air Force |accessdate=8 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303220847/http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/90squadron.cfm |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and [[No. 107 Squadron RAF|No. 107]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/104squadron.cfm |title=107 Squadron |website=Royal Air Force |accessdate=8 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170818132330/https://www.raf.mod.uk/history/104squadron.cfm |archive-date=2017-08-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Danny Murtaugh]], American baseball player and manager, second baseman for [[Philadelphia Phillies]], [[Boston Braves (baseball)|Boston Braves]] and [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] from 1941 to 1951, manager of the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] during the [[1960 World Series|1960]] and [[1971 World Series]], in [[Chester, Pennsylvania]] (d. [[1976]]); [[Billy Conn]], American boxer, [[Light heavyweight|world light heavyweight champion]] from 1939 to 1941, in [[Pittsburgh]] (d. [[1993]])\n* '''Born:''' [[Rodney Robert Porter]], English biochemist, recipient of the [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]] for his research on [[antibody|antibodies]], in [[Newton-le-Willows]], [[England]] (d. [[1985]]); [[Tex Banwell]], British army officer, served as political decoy for General [[Bernard Montgomery]] during [[World War Two]], in [[Newport, Essex]], [[England]] (d. [[1999]]); [[Walter Lord]], American writer, author of ''[[A Night to Remember (book)|A Night to Remember]]'', about the sinking of the [[RMS Titanic|RMS ''Titanic'']], in [[Baltimore]] (d. [[2002]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Ebenezer Ward]], Australian politician, member of the [[South Australian House of Assembly]] from 1870 to 1900 (b. [[1837]])\n\n== [[October 9]], 1917 (Tuesday) ==\n* [[Battle of Poelcappelle]] &ndash; German forces halted the British advance on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] in [[West Flanders]], [[Belgium]] but at a cost of 35,000 casualties during the first ten days of October. Total British and Commonwealth casualties for the day's fighting were around 11,500.<ref>{{cite book |series=History of the Great War Based on Official Documents by Direction of the Historical Section of the Committee of Imperial Defence |title= Military Operations France and Belgium 1917: 7 June\u201310 November Messines and Third Ypres (Passchendaele) |volume=II |last=Edmonds |first=J. E. |authorlink=James Edward Edmonds |year=1991 |orig-year=1948 |publisher=HMSO |edition=Imperial War Museum and Battery Press |location=London |isbn=978-0-89839-166-4|pages=334\u2013341}}</ref>\n* During the [[Battle of Poelcappelle]], a squad of 71 Australian soldiers with the [[10th Battalion (Australia)|10th Battalion]] [[Mystery of Celtic Wood|disappeared without a trace in Celtic Wood]] during a diversionary attack on German positions. Speculations of the unaccounted for men ranged from clerical error to the troops being massacred and buried in a mass grave (though German records made no mention of such an incident). Official Australian military document confirm at least 37 men remained unaccounted.<ref>{{citation |title=On this day: October 9 |publisher=defence.gov.au| url=http://www.defence.gov.au/army/ahu/On_This_Day/October/9_October.htm#1917 |archiveurl=http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/51715/20050801-0000/www.defence.gov.au/army/ahu/On_This_Day/October/9_October.htm#1917 |archivedate=1 August 2005}}</ref>\n* [[Royal Navy]] [[cruiser]] HMS ''Champagne'' was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Irish Sea]] by German submarine {{SMU|U-96||6}} with the loss of 58 of her 305 crew.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/wwi/ships_hit/1208.html |title=Champagne |publisher=Uboat.net |accessdate=29 December 2012}}</ref>\n* The [[U.S. Marines]] established the [[8th Marine Regiment]].<ref>[http://www.marzone.com/8thMarines/Hst2000.htm Lineage of the 8th Marine Regiment]{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* '''Died:''' [[Hussein Kamel of Egypt]], Egyptian noble, [[Sultan of Egypt]] from 1914 to 1917 (b. [[1853]]); [[Sarah Aaronsohn]], Jewish Palestinian spy, member of the [[Nili]] spy network, sister to botanist [[Aaron Aaronsohn]] (b. [[1890]])\n\n== [[October 10]], 1917 (Wednesday) ==\n* A coalition of Conservative, Liberal and independent members of [[Parliament of Canada|Canadian Parliament]] led by Prime Minister [[Robert Borden]] formed the [[Unionist Party (Canada)|Unionist Party of Canada]] to enact [[conscription]] and govern [[Canada]] through the remainder of [[World War One]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Armstrong|first1=Elizabeth|title=The Crisis of Quebec, 1914-1918|date=Jan 15, 1974|publisher=McGill-Queen's Press| location=Montreal| url=https://books.google.ca/books/about/The_Crisis_of_Quebec_1914_1918|accessdate=24 April 2016}}</ref>\n* The first novel of the science fiction series [[Barsoom]], ''[[A Princess of Mars]]'', by [[Edgar Rice Burroughs]] was published in hardcover by A.C. McClurg & Company.<ref>{{cite book |last=Porges |first=Irwin |title=Edgar Rice Burroughs |publisher=Brigham Young University Press |location=Provo, Utah |year=1975 |isbn=0-8425-0079-0 |page=[https://archive.org/details/edgarriceburroug00irwi/page/291 291] |url=https://archive.org/details/edgarriceburroug00irwi/page/291 }}</ref>\n* Norwegian sports club [[IF T\u00f8nsberg-Kameratene]] was established in [[T\u00f8nsberg]], [[Norway]] with sections for [[association football]], track and field, boxing, wrestling and weightlifting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tonsbergkameratene.no/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=26&Itemid=174|title=Litt om oss|publisher=IF T\u00f8nsberg-Kameratene|language=Norwegian|accessdate=28 July 2010}}</ref> \n* '''Born:''' [[Thelonious Monk]], American jazz musician, known for numerous jazz hits including \"[['Round Midnight (song)|'Round Midnight]]\", \"[[Blue Monk]]\", and \"[[Straight, No Chaser (composition)|Straight, No Chaser]]\", second most recorded jazz artist after [[Duke Ellington]], in [[Rocky Mount, North Carolina]] (d. [[1982]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Henry Crimmel]], American artisan, renowned glass-maker and co-founder of the [[Novelty Glass Company]] and [[Sneath Glass Company]] (b. [[1844]])\n\n== [[October 11]], 1917 (Thursday) ==\n* [[Operation Albion]] &ndash; A German amphibious force landed at [[Tagalaht]] on the island of [[Saaremaa]] in the Russian-controlled [[West Estonian archipelago]] in the [[Baltic Sea]] to capture the islands and stage a launching point to attack [[Petrograd]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Barrett |first=M. B. |url=http://www.iupress.indiana.edu/catalog/product_info.php?products_id=57467 |accessdate=24 March 2017 |title=Operation Albion: The German Conquest of the Baltic Islands |publisher=Indiana University Press |location=Bloomington, IN |year=2008 |isbn=978-0-253-34969-9|page=8}}</ref>\n* The [[Armenian National Congress (1917)|Armenian National Congress]] met in [[Tbilisi]], [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] to determine the role the Armenian population would play in post [[Imperial Russia]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Douglas|first=John M.|title=The Armenians|year=1992|publisher=J.J. Winthrop Corp.|location=New York, NY|isbn=9780963138101|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aIYlAQAAMAAJ&pg|accessdate=9 February 2013|page=358}}</ref>\n* The [[No. 41 Wing RAF|No. 41 Wing]] was established by the [[Royal Flying Corps]] with [[Lieutenant-Colonel]] [[Cyril Newall, 1st Baron Newall|Cyril Newall]] in command.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rafweb.org/Wings1.htm |title=Wing Nos 1 - 50 |accessdate=2008-07-17 |last=Barrass |first=Malcolm |date=2007-06-11 |work=Air of Authority - A History of RAF Organisation |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080726013531/http://www.rafweb.org/Wings1.htm |archivedate=2008-07-26 }}</ref>\n* The [[U.S. Army]] established the [[28th Infantry Division (United States)|28th]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/forcestruc/cbtchron/cc/028id.htm|title=Lineage and Honors Information: 28th Infantry Division |publisher=[[United States Army Center of Military History]] |accessdate=3 November 2009}}</ref> [[30th Infantry Division (United States)|30th]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/forcestruc/cbtchron/cc/030id.htm|title=Lineage and Honors Information: 30th Infantry Division |publisher=[[United States Army Center of Military History]] |accessdate=3 November 2009}}</ref> and [[31st Infantry Division (United States)|31st Infantry Divisions]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/forcestruc/cbtchron/cc/031id.htm|title=Lineage and Honors Information: 31st Infantry Division |publisher=[[United States Army Center of Military History]] |accessdate=3 November 2009}}</ref>\n* The [[Richmond Professional Institute]] was established in [[Richmond, Virginia]] as a medical and healthcare professional school.<ref>{{cite book |last = Hibbs |first = Henry |title = A History of the Richmond Professional Institute |publisher = RPI Foundation by Whittet & Shepperson |year = 1973 |page=16}}</ref>\n\n== [[October 12]], 1917 (Friday) ==\n* [[First Battle of Passchendaele]] &ndash; [[Allies of World War I|Allied]] forces failed to take key defensive ridges held by the Germans west of the village of [[Passendale|Passchendaele]], [[Belgium]].{{sfn|Edmonds|1991|pp=340\u2013344}} The brunt of the 13,000 casualties were taken by [[Australian and New Zealand Army Corps|ANZAC]] units, with the [[New Zealand]] division suffering 2,725 casualties including 845 killed, the single biggest loss for [[New Zealand]] (roughly one in 1,000 of the nation's population at that time).<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Dennis |editor1-first=P. |editor2-last=Grey |editor2-first=G. |title=1917: Tactics, Training and Technology |authorlink= |year=2007 |last=Harper |first=G. |chapter=Masterpiece or Massacre: the New Zealand Division and two Battles of 1917 |publisher=Australian History Military Publications |location=Loftus, NSW |edition= |isbn=978-0-9803-7967-9|page=69}}</ref> German casualties were estimated at 12,000.<ref>{{cite book |series=Weltkrieg 1914 bis 1918: Milit\u00e4rischen Operationen zu Lande |volume=XIII |title=Die Kriegf\u00fchrung im Sommer und Herbst 1917. Die Ereignisse au\u00dferhalb der Westfront bis November 1918 |trans-title=The War in Summer and Autumn, 1917. Events Beyond the Western Front until November, 1918 |language=German |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2012 |orig-year=1942 |publisher=Mittler |location=Berlin |url=https://digi.landesbibliothek.at/viewer/image/AC03617667/1/LOG_0003/ |accessdate=17 November 2012 |edition=Die digitale landesbibliotek Ober\u00f6sterreich |oclc=257129831 |page=96 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203013658/http://digi.landesbibliothek.at/viewer/image/AC03617667/1/LOG_0003/ |archive-date=2013-12-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Operation Albion]] &ndash; German forces captured 20,000 Russian prisoners and 100 guns as they expanded out from [[Tagalaht]] to the rest of the island of [[Saaremaa]] in the Baltic Sea.{{sfn|Barrett|2008|p=8}}\n* The first regiment was stationed at the newly commissioned Naval Operating Base in [[Norfolk, Virginia]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Hampton Roads Naval Historical Foundation|title=Images of America: Naval Station Norfolk|date=February 2014|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|location=Charleston, SC|pages=7}}</ref> \n* The Brazilian sports club [[Fonseca Atl\u00e9tico Clube|Fonseca]] was established in [[Niter\u00f3i]], [[Brazil]], and included [[association football]], martial arts, swimming and gymnastics.<ref>{{cite web| title=History| url=http://www.fonsecaatleticoclube.com.br/historia.html| website=Official Website of Fonseca Atl\u00e9tico Clube| language=Portuguese| url-status=bot: unknown| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140107192014/http://www.fonsecaatleticoclube.com.br/historia.html| archivedate=2014-01-07}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[James McAuley]], Australian poet and literary critic, known for poetry collections including ''A World of its own'' and literary criticism such as ''The rhetoric of Australian poetry'', in [[Lakemba, New South Wales]], [[Australia]] (d. [[1976]])\n* '''Died:''' [[George Augustus King]], New Zealand army officer, commander of the [[New Zealand (M\u0101ori) Pioneer Battalion|New Zealand Pioneer Battalion]] (killed at the [[Battle of Passchendaele]]) (b. [[1885]]); [[Clarence Jeffries]], Australian army officer, recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]] (killed at the [[Battle of Passchendaele]]) (b. [[1894]]); [[Lewis McGee (soldier)|Lewis McGee]], Australian soldier, recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]] for action during the [[Battle of Broodseinde]] (killed at the [[Battle of Passchendaele]]) (b. [[1888]])\n\n== [[October 13]], 1917 (Saturday) ==\n* [[Miracle of the Sun]] &ndash; A massive gathering of pilgrims in [[F\u00e1tima, Portugal]], estimated between 30,000 and 40,000 (with another report going as high as 100,000) simultaneously witnessed the sun change colors and move in impossible paths across the sky for ten minutes. The miraculous event was foretold by local children [[L\u00facia dos Santos]] and siblings [[Jacinta and Francisco Marto]], who had been experiencing visions from [[Our Lady of F\u00e1tima]] for months.<ref>{{cite book|first = John | last = De Marchi | date = 1952b | title = The Immaculate Heart, The True Story of Our Lady of Fatima| publisher = Farrar, Straus and Young | location = New York|oclc = 2947238 |pages=151\u201366}}</ref> After years of investigation, the [[Catholic Church]] concluded in 1930 that the event was genuine but skeptics have cited mass delusion brought on by weeks of speculation or meteorological illusions as the cause.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.miraclehunter.com/marian_apparitions/statements/fatima_statement_02.html|title=Results of the Investigative Commission| date=October 1930| accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Skeptoid|id=4110|number=110|title=Illuminating the Fatima Miracle of the Sun|date=July 22, 2008|accessdate=16 April 2017}}</ref>\n* Tire manufacturer [[Yokohama Rubber Company|Yokohama]] was established in [[Tokyo]] as a joint venture between Yokohama Cable Manufacturing and [[Goodrich Corporation|B.F. Goodrich]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Establishment of The Yokohama Rubber Co., Ltd.|url=http://www.y-yokohama.com/global/100th/history/|website=yokohama.com|publisher=Yokohama|accessdate=30 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170331090639/http://www.y-yokohama.com/global/100th/history/|archive-date=31 March 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* The [[United States Oil & Gas Association]] was established in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]] which at the time was considered the \"Oil Capital of the World\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usoga.org/en/about_us/history/|title=A Brief History|publisher=usoga.org|accessdate=May 26, 2014}}</ref>\n* The city of [[South Euclid, Ohio]] was incorporated.<ref>[http://www.cityofsoutheuclid.com/about.htm About South Euclid] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061206004420/http://www.cityofsoutheuclid.com/about.htm |date=2006-12-06 }}, City of South Euclid, Ohio. Retrieved December 29, 2006</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[George Osmond]], American entertainer, patriarch of [[The Osmonds]] family singing group, in [[Etna, Wyoming]] (d. [[2007]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Florence La Badie]], American actress, best known for work in the film serial ''[[The Million Dollar Mystery]]'' in which she performed her own stunts (killed in a car accident) (b. [[1888]])\n\n== [[October 14]], 1917 (Sunday) ==\n* British cargo ship SS ''Semantha'' was torpedoed and sunk in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] by German submarine {{SMU|UC-74||6}} with the loss of 32 of her crew.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/wwi/ships_hit/5516.html |title=Semantha |publisher=Uboat.net |accessdate=28 December 2012}}</ref>\n* German submarine {{SMU|UC-62||6}} struck a mine and sank in the [[North Sea]] with the loss of all 26 crew.<ref>{{cite Uboat.net|name=UC 62|id=UC+62 |type=1sub|accessdate=23 February 2009}}</ref>\n* The [[Uruguay national football team]] won its second [[1917 South American Championship|South American Championship]], defeating [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] 1-0 in the series final in [[Parque Pereira]], [[Montevideo]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Southamerican Championship 1917|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/17safull.html|website=RSSSF.com|accessdate=5 June 2017}}</ref>\n* The [[St. Clements Roman Catholic Church (Saratoga Springs, New York)|St. Clements Roman Catholic Church]] held first [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]] in [[Saratoga Springs, New York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stclementschurch.com/our-parish/our-parish/|work=St. Clement's Church|title=The First Mass \u2014 As told from history of St. Clement's Parish|accessdate=December 16, 2012}}</ref>\n* The historic drama ''[[Cleopatra (1917 film)|Cleopatra]]'' was released, with [[Theda Bara]] in the starring role as the Egyptian queen. Directed by [[J. Gordon Edwards]], the film also starred [[Fritz Leiber (actor)|Fritz Leiber]] as [[Julius Caesar]] and [[Thurston Hall]] as [[Mark Antony]]. Controversy around its sensual images only made the film more popular the biggest hit of 1917.<ref>{{cite book|last1=McCaffrey|first1=Donald W.|last2=Jacobs|first2=Christopher P.|title=Guide to the Silent Years of American Cinema|year=1999|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=0-313-30345-2|page=[https://archive.org/details/guidetosilentyea00mcca/page/82 82]|url=https://archive.org/details/guidetosilentyea00mcca/page/82}}</ref> The film was considered lost but some fragments along with production stills survived, allowing a portion of the film to be reconstructed for screening at the [[Hollywood Heritage Museum]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ziemba|first1=Christine N.|title=Twenty Of The Coolest Events Happening in L.A. This Week|url=http://laist.com/2017/02/06/20_of_the_coolest_events_happening_2.php|accessdate=9 March 2017|agency=Laist|date=February 6, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170501083710/http://laist.com/2017/02/06/20_of_the_coolest_events_happening_2.php|archivedate=1 May 2017}}</ref>\n* The Argentine [[association football]] club [[Almirante Brown de Arrecifes]] was established in [[Arrecifes]], [[Argentina]].<ref>[http://www.clarin.com/deportes/Querido_Ascenso_0_278972304.html \"Brown de Arrecifes: un viaje de ida y vuelta\"], Clar\u00edn web, 2010-06-11</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Geoffrey Bibby]], English [[archaeologist]], best known for the discovery of the ancient city of [[Dilmun]] and the pioneer of Arabian archaeology, in [[Heversham]], [[England]] (d. [[2001 in archaeology|2001]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Nathaniel Hone the Younger]], Irish painter, member of the [[Hone family]] (b. [[1831 in art|1831]]); [[Eddie Latheron]], English [[association football]] player, [[inside forward]] for the [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.]] from 1906 to 1917 and the [[England national football team]] from 1913 to 1914 (killed at the [[Battle of Passchendaele]]) (b. [[1887]])\n\n== [[October 15]], 1917 (Monday) ==\n* [[Battle of Mahiwa]] &ndash; Nigerian colonial troops under command of [[General]] [[Jacob van Deventer (general)|Jacob van Deventer]] fought German colonial soldiers under command of [[Major-General]] [[Kurt Wahle]] at [[Mahiwa, Tanzania|Mahiwa]], [[German East Africa]] (now [[Tanzania]]). General [[Paul von Lettow-Vorbeck]], commander of forces in [[German East Africa]], sent additional battalions that encircled the Nigerian force.<ref>{{cite book| last=Paice|first=Edward|title=Tip & Run: The Untold Tragedy of the Great War in Africa| origyear=2007| year=2008| publisher=Phoenix| location=London| isbn=978-0-7538-2349-1|page=330}}</ref>\n* The first [[Action of 15 October 1917|naval action]] between the [[U.S. Navy]] and [[Imperial German Navy]] occurred when American destroyer [[USS Cassin (DD-43)|USS ''Cassin'']] exchanged fire with German submarine [[SM U-61|SM ''U-61'']] off the coast of [[Ireland]], with both vessels damaged. The sole casualty was U.S. sailor [[Osmond Ingram]], who jettisoned several depth charges from a point where a German torpedo was about to hit, saving the ship from catastrophic damage. He was awarded the [[Medal of Honor]] posthumously, and was the first recorded enlisted American casualty of [[World War One]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/photos/pers-us/uspers-i/o-ingram.htm |title=Gunner's Mate First Class Osmond K. Ingram, USN, (1887-1917) |author= |date=20 November 2007 |website= |publisher=Naval Historical Center |accessdate=23 February 2012}}</ref>\n* Dutch dancer [[Mata Hari]] was executed by [[firing squad]] at [[Vincennes]] outside [[Paris]] for [[espionage|spying]] on behalf of [[Germany]].<ref>[http://www.eyewitnesstohistory.com/matahari.htm Execution of Mata Hari]. Eyewitnesstohistory.com (19 October 1917). Retrieved on 2011-10-15.</ref>\n* The [[Chicago White Sox]] defeated the [[New York Giants (NL)|New York Giants]] to win the [[1917 World Series|World Series]] by four games to two.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cohen|first1=Richard M.|last2=Neft|first2=David S.|title=The World Series: Complete Play-By-Play of Every Game, 1903\u20131989|date=1990|publisher=St. Martin's Press.|location=New York|isbn=0-312-03960-3|pages=[https://archive.org/details/worldseries0000cohe/page/66 66\u201370]|url=https://archive.org/details/worldseries0000cohe/page/66}}</ref>\n* [[Royal Navy]] air officer [[John Alcock (RAF officer)|John Alcock]] oversaw the first test flight of his experimental fighter biplane, named the [[Alcock Scout]]. However, only one had been made and when it crashed on another test flight in 1918, no further models were built.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bruce|first=J.M.|title=War Planes of the First World War: Volume One Fighters|year=1965|publisher=Macdonald|location=London|page=8}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Alan W. Livingston]], American music and television producer, best known for the television western ''[[Bonanza]]'' and the creation of [[Bozo the Clown]], founder of [[Capitol Records]], in [[McDonald, Pennsylvania]] (d. [[2009]]); [[Jan Miner]], American actress, best known as Madge in the television [[Colgate-Palmolive]] commercials, in [[Boston]] (d. [[2004]]); [[Arthur M. Schlesinger Jr.]], American historian, recipient for the [[Pulitzer Prize for Biography or Autobiography]] for his historic volume ''[[A Thousand Days]]'' on the [[Presidency of John F. Kennedy]], in [[Columbus, Ohio]] (d. [[2007]])\n* '''Born:''' [[Ruair\u00ed Brugha]], Irish politician, member of the [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] (Irish Parliament) from 1962 to 1982, in [[Dublin]]) (d. [[2006]]); [[Kevin Boland]], Irish politician, cabinet minister for the [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann|Irish Assembly]] from 1965 to 1976, in [[Dublin]] (d. [[2001]]); [[Adele Stimmel Chase]], American artist, best known for her ceramics works that became part of [[Pop art]] and [[Op art]] movements, in [[San Francisco]] (d. [[2000]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Maxime Collignon]], French archaeologist, known for his research in ancient Greek art and architecture (b. [[1849 in archaeology|1849]])\n\n== [[October 16]], 1917 (Tuesday) ==\n* The first [[1917 Dutch East Indies Volksraad election|free elections]] in the [[Dutch East Indies]] were held.<ref>Karel Steenbrink (2007) ''The spectacular growth of a self confident minority, 1903 - 1942'' KITLV Press, p. 44</ref>\n* [[Battle of Moon Sound]] &ndash; British submarines engaged but failed to halt the progress of a German naval squadron dispatched to control the [[Baltic Sea]] around the [[West Estonian archipelago]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Staff|first=Gary|title=Operation Albion| url=http://www.gwpda.org/naval/albion3.htm| accessdate=October 18, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Battle of Mahiwa]] &ndash; South African reinforcements attacked German troops from the opposing side, but the Germans regrouped to a ridge near [[Mahiwa, Tanzania|Mahiwa]] to hold off the attacks.<ref>Paice 2008, p. 330</ref>\n* [[Operation Albion]] &ndash; German forces won complete control of the island of [[Saaremaa]] in the [[Baltic Sea]].{{sfn|Barrett|2008|p=8}} \n* '''Born:''' [[Alice Pearce]], American actress, best known as [[Gladys Kravitz]] in the 1960s television sitcom ''[[Bewitched]]'' in which she won an [[Emmy]] posthumously, in [[New York City]] (d. [[1966]]); [[Murray MacLehose, Baron MacLehose of Beoch|Murray MacLehose]], British colonial administrator, 25th [[Governor of Hong Kong]], in [[Glasgow]] (d. [[2000]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Walter Flex]], German writer, author of ''The Wanderer between the Two Worlds'' (killed in action) (b. [[1887]])\n\n== [[October 17]], 1917 (Wednesday) ==\n* German [[light cruiser]]s {{SMS|Brummer||2}} and {{SMS|Bremse||2}} [[Action off Lerwick|ambushed]] an [[Allies of World War I|Allied]] convoy in the [[North Sea]], sinking British [[destroyer]]s {{HMS|Mary Rose|1915|2}} and {{HMS|Strongbow|1916|2}} along with several Scandinavian merchant ships carrying coal. Over 300 naval and civilian crew were killed in the attack.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=German naval raid. |day_of_week=Monday |date=22 October 1917 |page_number=8 |issue=41615 |column=C-D }}</ref>\n* [[Battle of Moon Sound]] &ndash; German and Russian naval squadrons clashed in the Baltic Sea, ending with a Russian retreat and the loss of its [[pre-dreadnought]] ship ''Slava'', which was too damaged to retreat and had to be scuttled.<ref>Staff 2012</ref>\n* [[U.S. Army]] troopship [[SS Antilles (1907)|USAT ''Antilles'']] was torpedoed and damaged in the [[Bay of Biscay]] by German submarine {{SMU|U-105||6}} with the loss of 67 lives. Survivors were rescued by {{USS|Corsair|SP-159|6}} before the ship was scuttled.<ref>{{cite DANFS | title=Corsair| url=http://www.hazegray.org/danfs/patrol/corsair.htm |accessdate=2 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/wwi/ships_hit/359.html |title=Antilles |publisher=Uboat.net |accessdate=25 October 2012}}</ref>\n* The [[Trans-Australian Railway]] opened, linking 1,052 miles (1,693&nbsp;km) of railroad between [[Port Augusta, South Australia|Port Augusta]] in [[South Australia]] and [[Kalgoorlie]] in [[Western Australia]]. The rail included 309 miles (497&nbsp;km) of straight rail with no curves across the [[Nullarbor Plain]], making it the world\u2019s longest railway straight.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Golden Jubilee of the Trans Australian Railway| author=Chambers, T.F. |journal=[[Australian Railway History]] |pages=267\u201375 |date=November 1968}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| last=Burke| first=David| year=1991|title=Road through the Wilderness: the story of the transcontinental railway, the first great work of Australia's federation| location=Kensington|publisher=New South Wales University Press|isbn=0-86840-140-4}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Ferneyhough|first=Frank|title=The History of Railways in Britain|location=Reading|publisher=Osprey|year=1975|isbn=0-85045-060-8}}</ref>\n* The [[Co-operative Party]] was formed as the official political party of the [[British co-operative movement]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=James C. Docherty|author2=Peter Lamb|title=Historical Dictionary of Socialism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JRYjU-L4F7wC&pg=PA90|year=2006|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-6477-1|page=90}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Arthur Birnie|title=An Economic History of the British Isles|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9UL-AQAAQBAJ&pg=PA367|year=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-58979-9|page=367}}</ref>\n* The German [[association football]] club [[BC Aichach]] was established in [[Aichach]], [[Germany]].<ref>[http://www.bc-aichach.de/ Chronik des BC Aichach] {{in lang|de}} BC Aichach website, accessed: 8 November 2011</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Martin Donnelly (cricketer)|Martin Donnelly]], New Zealand cricketer, member of the [[New Zealand national cricket team]] in 1937, in [[Ngaruawahia]], [[New Zealand]] (d. [[1999]]); [[Dick Young (sportswriter)|Dick Young]], American sports journalist, baseball columnist for the ''[[New York Daily News]]'' for 45 years (d. [[1987]])\n* '''Born:''' [[Marsha Hunt (actress, born 1917)|Marsha Hunt]], American actress, known for her roles in ''[[Born to the West]]'', ''[[These Glamour Girls]]'', and ''[[Johnny Got His Gun (film)|Johnny Got His Gun]]'', member of the [[Committee for the First Amendment]] during the Hollywood blacklist, in [[Chicago]]; [[Sumner Locke Elliott]], Australian writer, author of ''[[Careful, He Might Hear You (novel)|Careful, He Might Hear You]]'' and ''[[Rusty Bugles]]'', in [[Sydney]] (d. [[1991]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Bobby Atherton]], Welsh [[association football]] player, midfielder and forward for various clubs including [[Hibernian F.C.]] and [[Middlesbrough F.C.]] from 1897 to 1906, member of the [[Wales national football team]] from 1899 to 1905 (missing in action) (b. [[1876]]); [[John Franklin Botume]], American singer and choir director, author on several books on singing including ''Modern Singing Methods: Their Use and Abuse'' (b. [[1855]])\n\n== [[October 18]], 1917 (Thursday) ==\n* [[Battle of Mahiwa]] &ndash; A German force of 1,500 men counterattacked and repelled the attacking South African and Nigerian force of 4,900 men, inflicting 2,700 casualties. The Germans suffered between 500-600 casualties, or thirty percent of its strength.<ref>Paice 2008, pp. 331-332</ref> \n* [[Operation Albion]] &ndash; Russian forces evacuated from [[Muhu]] in the [[Baltic Sea]].{{sfn|Barrett|2008|p=8}}\n* '''Born:''' [[Robert A. Lewis]], American air force officer, co-pilot of the ''[[Enola Gay]]'' that dropped the first [[A-bomb]] on [[Hiroshima]], in [[Ridgefield Park, New Jersey]] (d. [[1983]])\n\n== [[October 19]], 1917 (Friday) ==\n* [[Operation Albion]] &ndash; German forces landed at [[Hiiumaa]] Island in the [[Baltic Sea]].{{sfn|Barrett|2008|p=8}}\n* [[Battle of Moon Sound]] &ndash; German ships entered the Gulf of Riga and began to clear the minefield, where most casualties occurred during the operation.<ref>Staff 2012</ref>\n* Thirteen Zeppelins set out on a high-altitude raid against the middle of [[England]] but severe weather conditions prevented all but two in reaching their targets. One of the airships bombed [[London]], killing 24 people and injuring nine others, as well destroying the [[Austin Motor Company|Austin Motor Works]] plant at [[Longbridge]], [[England]]. The second airship bombed [[Northampton]] and [[London]], killing 24 people and injuring nine others.<ref>Whitehouse 1966, pp. 223-232, 236, 243</ref>\n* [[Carl Swartz]] left office as [[Prime Minister of Sweden]] after dismal election results for the right-wing party in the September [[Riksdag]] elections. He was replaced by liberal leader [[Nils Ed\u00e9n]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Sweden.html|title=Sweden|publisher=World Statesmen|language=Swedish|accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref>\n* American [[ocean liner]] {{SS|J. L. Luckenbach||2}} was torpedoed and damaged in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] by German submarine {{SMU|U-62||6}}. She was escorted to [[Le Havre]], [[Seine-Maritime]], [[France]] by [[U.S. Navy]] [[destroyer]] {{USS|Nicholson|DD-52|6}} where she was subsequently repaired and returned to service.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Sims | first1 = William Sowden | last2 = Hendrick | first2 = Burton Jesse | authorlink1 = William Sims | authorlink2 = Burton J. Hendrick | title = The Victory at Sea | location = [[Garden City, New York]] | publisher = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday, Page & Co.]] | year = 1920 | oclc = 1058119 | pages = 148\u201349 | title-link = The Victory at Sea }}</ref>\n* [[Dallas Love Field]] was opened in [[Dallas]] as a military base for training pilots enlisted in [[World War One]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.archives.gov/research/guide-fed-records/groups/018.html#18.5.4|title=Records of the Army Air Forces [AAF]| website=Archives.gov| accessdate=June 10, 2016}}</ref>\n* The ''[[Luftstreitkr\u00e4fte]]'', the air arm of the [[Imperial German Army]], established air squadron ''[[Jagdstaffel 80]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theaerodrome.com/services/germany/jasta/jasta80.php |title=Jasta 80 |work=The Aerodrome |year=2015 |accessdate=18 December 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* The [[Institute of Quarrying]] was established during a meeting of quarry managers in [[Caernarfon]], [[Wales]]. The organization expanded with branches in [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], [[Malaysia]], [[South Africa]] and [[Hong Kong]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Institute of Quarrying Timeline| url=http://www.quarrying.org/about-us/iq-timeline|website=Quarrying.org|publisher=Institute of Quarrying|accessdate=8 April 2017}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Walter Munk]], Austrian-American oceanographer, best known for his tidal research into oceans and ocean currents with the [[Scripps Institution of Oceanography]], in [[Vienna]] (d. [[2019]]); [[Evgenia Antipova]], Russian artist, member of the [[Leningrad School of Painting]], in [[Toropets]], [[Russia]] (d. [[2009]]); [[Robert P. Baldwin]], American air force pilot, recipient of the [[Silver Star]] and [[Legion of Merit]] for action during the [[Korean War]], in [[Los Angeles]] (d. [[1994]])\n\n== [[October 20]], 1917 (Saturday) ==\n* [[Operation Albion]] &ndash; German forces occupied all of [[Hiiumaa]] Island in the [[Baltic Sea]], ending the campaign.{{sfn|Barrett|2008|p=8}}\n* British cargo ship ''{{SS|Mahratta|1917|2}}'' was launched by Robert Duncan & Co in [[Port Glasgow]], [[Scotland]]. In a remarkable coincidence, the ship was wrecked in the [[English Channel]] in the exact spot as its predecessor.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.clydesite.co.uk/clydebuilt/viewship.asp?id=17059 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526062555/http://www.clydesite.co.uk/clydebuilt/viewship.asp?id=17059 | url-status=usurped | archive-date=2011-05-26 |title=Launched 1917: ss MAHRATTA |publisher=clydesite |accessdate=2008-11-08}}</ref>\n* Police in [[Washington D.C.]] arrested [[Alice Paul]], a prominent member of the suffragist protest group [[Silent Sentinels]], while she carried a banner that quoted [[U.S. President]] [[Woodrow Wilson]]: \"The time has come to conquer or submit, for us there can be but one choice. We have made it.\" Paul was sentenced to seven months in prison where, after enduring two weeks of solitary confinement, was released to prison hospital where she started a hunger strike to protest the poor conditions of the [[Virginia]] penitentiary where many fellow Sentinel members were also imprisoned.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Stevens|first1=Doris|title=Jailed for Freedom|date=1920|publisher=Liverright Publishing|location=New York, NY}}</ref>\n* Irish poet [[W. B. Yeats]], then 51, married 25-year-old [[Georgie Hyde-Lees]] at the [[Harrow Road]] [[register office]] in [[London]] with [[Ezra Pound]] as best man. It had been a couple of months after he had a proposal of marriage to his ex-mistress's daughter, [[Iseult Gonne]], rejected.<ref>Cahill, Christopher. \"Second Puberty: The Later Years of W. B. Yeats Brought His Best Poetry, along with Personal Melodrama on an Epic Scale\". ''The Atlantic Monthly'', December 2003.</ref> \n* The [[U.S. Army]] established the [[Aberdeen Proving Ground]] in [[Aberdeen, Maryland]] as an ordinance testing site.<ref>{{cite web|title=History of APG|url=http://armyalliance.org/about-apg/history-of-apg/|website=Army Alliance|accessdate=3 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170429091304/http://armyalliance.org/about-apg/history-of-apg/|archive-date=29 April 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Jean-Pierre Melville]], French film director, best known for his [[French New Wave]] crime dramas ''[[Le Doulos]]'', ''[[Le Samoura\u00ef]]'', and ''[[Le Cercle rouge]]'', in [[Paris]] (d. [[1973]]); [[William F. Barnes]], American college football player and coach, served as coach for the [[UCLA Bruins football]] team from 1958 to 1964, in [[Cape Girardeau, Missouri]] (d. [[2009]]); [[St\u00e9phane Hessel]], German-French diplomat and Holocaust survivor, author of ''[[Time for Outrage!]]'', in [[Berlin]] (d. [[2013]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Elise Kemp]], New Zealand nurse, only military nurse from the country to be killed in action in [[World War One]] (b. [[1881]]); [[John T. Wilder]], American army officer, Union commander at the [[Battle of Hoover's Gap]] during the [[American Civil War]] (b. [[1830]])\n\n== [[October 21]], 1917 (Sunday) ==\n* [[Malta]] held a [[1917 Maltese general election|general election]] for six out of its eight seats.<ref>Michael J Schiavone (1987) ''L-Elezzjonijiet F'Malta 1849\u20131981'', Pubblikazzjoni Bugelli, p.19</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Dizzy Gillespie]], American jazz trumpet musician, credited for the development of [[bebop]] and promotion of [[Afro-Cuban music]], in [[Cheraw, South Carolina]] (d. [[1993]])\n\n== [[October 22]], 1917 (Monday) ==\n* British forces launched two [[Action of 22 October 1917|separate assaults]] on the German front in [[Belgium]], capturing the village of [[Langemark-Poelkapelle|Polecappelle]] but failing to seize a key road junction north of [[Houthulst]] Forest from German control.<ref>{{cite book |title=To Play a Giant's Part: The Role of the British Army at Passchendaele |last=Perry |first=R. A. |authorlink= |year=2014 |publisher=Naval & Military Press |location=Uckfield |edition= |isbn=978-1-78331-146-0|pages=470\u2013480}}</ref> British casualties were 479 while German casualties were unknown, save for 125 prisoners.{{sfn|Epdmonds|1991|=348}}\n* U.S. President [[Woodrow Wilson]] appointed [[A. Mitchell Palmer]] to head the [[Office of Alien Property Custodian]] which administered property seized from those deemed an enemy of the [[United States]] during [[World War One]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Coben|first1=Stanley|title=A. Mitchell Palmer: Politician|date=1963|publisher=Columbia University Press|location=New York|pages=128\u2013135}}</ref>\n* The [[Charlie Chaplin]]-directed film ''[[The Adventurer (1917 film)|The Adventurer]]'', starring Chaplin regulars [[Edna Purviance]] and [[Eric Campbell (actor)|Eric Campbell]], was released through [[Mutual Film]]. It was the last film by Campbell before his death in a car accident two months later.<ref>{{cite web|title=Charlie Chaplin's \"The Adventurer\" (1917)|url=https://archive.org/details/CC_1917_10_22_TheAdventurer|via=[[Internet Archive]] |accessdate=19 February 2013}}</ref>\n* The [[Sherlock Holmes]] anthology of previously published stories ''[[His Last Bow (short story)|His Last Bow]]'' included the newest short story of the same name by [[Arthur Conan Doyle]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sshf.com/encyclopedia/index.php/His_Last_Bow |title=His Last Bow |website=De Encyclop\u00e9die de Conan doyle & Sherlock Holmes |publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Sherlock Holmes de France |accessdate=21 January 2014}}</ref>\n* The first section of the [[Seibu Tamagawa Line]] for [[Tokyo]] opened for service.<ref>{{cite book |last = Terada |first = Hirokazu |title = \u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d6\u30c3\u30af\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u79c1\u9244 |trans-title= Databook: Japan's Private Railways |publisher = Neko Publishing |date = 19 January 2013 |location = Japan |page =227 |isbn = 978-4-7770-1336-4}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Joan Fontaine]], British-American actress, known for her roles in ''[[Rebecca (1940 film)|Rebecca]]'', ''[[Jane Eyre (1943 film)|Jane Eyre]]'' and ''[[The Constant Nymph (1943 film)|The Constant Nymph]]'', recipient of the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]] for her role in ''[[Suspicion (1941 film)|Suspicion]]'', sister to [[Olivia de Havilland]], in [[Tokyo]] (d. [[2013]]) \n* '''Died:''' [[Bob Fitzsimmons]], British boxer, held world champion titles in all three major weight classes, considered the lightest heavyweight champion in the ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' (b. [[1863]])\n\n== [[October 23]], 1917 (Tuesday) ==\n* [[Battle of La Malmaison]] &ndash; The [[Sixth Army (France)|French Sixth Army]] attacked the German-held French village and fort of [[La Malmaison]], [[France]], capturing the communes of [[Allemant, Marne|Allemant]] and [[Vaudesson]].<ref>{{cite book| title=The Times History of the War | volume=XVI| year=1914\u20131921| publisher=The Times| location=London| accessdate=29 June 2014| oclc=70406275| pages=234\u2013241| url=https://archive.org/details/timeshistoryofwa16londuoft}}</ref>\n* [[Battle of Wadi Musa]] &ndash; A force of 700 Arab rebel troops ambushed an Ottoman column dispatched to secure the [[Hejaz]] railway in [[Jordan]], killing 400 men and capturing 300 prisoners.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Murphy|first1=David|title=The Arab Revolt 1916\u201318 Lawrence sets Arabia Ablaze|date=2008|publisher=Osprey|location=London|isbn=978-1-84603-339-1|pages=56\u201357}}</ref>\n* [[October Revolution]] &ndash; The [[Bolshevik Party]] voted in favor of overthrowing the [[Russian Provisional Government]], with a resolution citing \"an armed uprising is inevitable, and that the time for it is fully ripe.\"<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.marxists.org/archive/lenin/works/1917/oct/10a.htm| title=Central Committee Meeting\u201410 Oct 1917}}</ref>\n* The Canadian Railway War Board (predecessor of the [[Railway Association of Canada]]) met for the first time at [[Windsor Station (Montreal)|Windsor Station]] in [[Montreal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railways.incanada.net/candate/candate.htm|title=Significant dates in Canadian railway history|work=Colin Churcher's Railway Pages|date=2006-09-15|accessdate=2006-10-23|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061023182151/http://www.railways.incanada.net/candate/candate.htm|archivedate=23 October 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/releases/archive/October2007/23/c7258.html|title=Historic Anniversary for the Railway Association of Canada|date=2007-10-23|accessdate=2007-10-23|publisher=Railway Association of Canada}}</ref>\n* The German government established the Reich Economic Office, the predecessor to the [[Federal Ministry for Economic Affairs and Energy]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The history of the Federal Ministry of Economics and Energy| url=http://www.bmwi.de/Navigation/DE/Ministerium/Geschichte/geschichte.html| website=BMWi| language=German}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Robert Bray]], American actor, best known for the role of ranger [[Corey Stuart]] in the TV series ''[[Lassie (1954 TV series)|Lassie]]'', in [[Kalispell, Montana]] (d. [[1983]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Eug\u00e8ne Grasset]], Swiss artist, pioneer of [[Art Nouveau]] (b. [[1845 in art|1845]])\n\n== [[October 24]], 1917 (Wednesday) ==\n* [[Battle of Caporetto]] &ndash; Also known as the Twelfth Battle of the Isonzo, Austro-Hungarian and German forces triggered 894 canisters that released chlorine gas onto the [[Second Army (Italy)|Italian Second Army]] entrenched in the valley. Most Italian soldiers retreated as their supplied gas masks could only last for two hours, with an estimated 500 to 600 defenders killed.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Stearns |first1=Peter |last2=Langer |first2=William|title=The Encyclopedia of World History |edition=6th |year=2001 |publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt |isbn=0-395-65237-5 |page=669}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Haber |first=Leonard |title=The Poisonous Cloud: Chemical Warfare in the First World War |year=1986 |publisher= Clarendon Press |isbn=0198581424 |page=186}}</ref> The [[Central Powers]] then used [[infiltration tactics]] and [[stormtroopers]] armed with light machine guns, mortar launchers, grenades and flamethrowers to break through the line, leading to its collapse six days later.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gudmundsson|first=Bruce|title=Stormtroop Tactics. Innovation in the German Army, 1914\u20131918|year=1989|publisher=Praeger|isbn=0-275-93328-8|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/briefhistoryofka00kamm}}</ref><ref>Seth, Ronald (1965). ''Caporetto: The Scapegoat Battle''. Macdonald. p. 147</ref> \n* The [[No. 190 Squadron RAF|No. 190 Squadron]] was established by the [[Royal Flying Corps]] at [[Rochford]], [[England]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/190squadron.cfm |title=190 Squadron |website=Royal Air Force |accessdate=8 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304043046/http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/190squadron.cfm |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Australian Flying Corps]] established air squadrons [[No. 7 Squadron RAAF|No. 7]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.airforce.gov.au/raafmuseum/research/units/7sqn.htm |title=No 7 Squadron, Royal Australian Air Force |publisher=RAAF Museum |accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref> and [[No. 8 Squadron RAAF|No. 8]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.airforce.gov.au/raafmuseum/research/units/8sqn.htm |title=No 8 Squadron, Royal Australian Air Force |publisher=RAAF Museum |accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref>\n* Telephone inventor [[Alexander Graham Bell]] attended the unveiling of a [[Bell Memorial|monument]] to him in front of a crowd of thousands in [[Brantford]], [[Ontario]].<ref>{{citation |last=McMeal |first=Harry B. |title=Unveiling of Bell Memorial at Brantford, Ontario, Ca. | publisher=Telephone Pub. Corp. |year=1917 |volume=73 |page=21}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Denys Val Baker]], Welsh writer, author of ''The Door is Always Open'' and ''The Sea\u2019s in The Kitchen'', in [[Upper Poppleton]], [[England]] (d. [[1984]]); [[Donald N. Aldrich]], American marine officer, recipient of the [[Navy Cross]] and [[Air Medal]] for action in the [[Solomon Islands campaign]] during [[World War Two]], in [[Moline, Illinois]] (d. [[1947]], killed in a plane crash)\n* '''Died:''' [[James Carroll Beckwith]], American artist, member of the [[Naturalism (art)|Naturalism]] movement in the [[United States]] (b. [[1852]])\n\n== [[October 25]], 1917 (Thursday) ==\n* The [[Petrograd Military Revolutionary Committee]] was established with [[Leon Trotsky]] as leader to organize the overthrow of the [[Russian Provisional Government]].<ref>{{cite book| last1=Suny| first1=Ronald| title=The Soviet Experiment| date=2011| publisher=Oxford University Press| pages=63\u201367}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title=Military Revolutionary Committees| url=http://bse.sci-lib.com/article005983.html| website=Great Soviet Encyclopedia|accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref>\n* Some 1,700 [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] delegates attended a convention in the [[Mansion House, Dublin|Dublin Mansion House]] as [[Arthur Griffith]] was replaced as the organisation's president with [[\u00c9amon de Valera]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Packenham|first1=Frank|title=\u00c9amon de Valera|date=1974|publisher=Arrow Books|page=68|url=https://books.google.com/?id=r7MMAQAAMAAJ&q=%22no+contemplation+in+it%22|accessdate=7 April 2016}}</ref>\n* The French Lyceum was established in [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb]], [[Albania]], later renamed the [[Albanian National Lyceum]] in 1921 and the [[Raqi Qirinxhi High School]] in 1944.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bashkiakorce.gov.al/frontend/article.php?aid=142&cid=51 |title=Liceu Francez i Korces |last=Municipality of Korce web page |language=Albanian |accessdate=3 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100116061312/http://www.bashkiakorce.gov.al/frontend/article.php?aid=142&cid=51 |archivedate=16 January 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Carl Forssell]], Swedish fencer, bronze medalist in the [[1948 Summer Olympics]] and silver medalist in the [[1952 Summer Olympics]], in [[Stockholm]] (d. [[2005]]); [[Lee MacPhail]], American sports executive, president and general manager of the [[Baltimore Orioles]] and [[New York Yankees]], and president of the [[American League]], son to [[Larry MacPhail]], in [[Nashville, Tennessee]] (d. [[2012]]); [[William Remington]], American economist, convicted of perjury stemming from espionage charges made by Soviet spy [[Elizabeth Bentley]], in [[New York City]] (d. [[1954]], murdered in prison) \n* '''Died:''' [[Jack Standing]], English actor, best known for his [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] roles including ''[[The Belle of New York (musical)|The Belle of New York]]'' and ''[[Florodora]]'', and his film roles such as ''[[Hell's Hinges]]'' (b. [[1886]]); [[Maximilian Bayer]], German army officer, founder of [[Scouting and Guiding in Germany|Scouting in Germany]] and the [[27th J\u00e4ger Battalion (Finland)|27th J\u00e4ger Battalion]] for the [[Imperial German Army]] (killed in action) (b. [[1872]])\n\n== [[October 26]], 1917 (Friday) ==\n* [[Brazil]] [[Brazil during World War I|declared war]] against [[Germany]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Brazil Proclaims War On Germany| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1917/10/27/archives/brazil-proclaims-war-on-germany-president-braz-announces.html|accessdate=8 October 2017|work=The New York Times|issue=October 27, 1917|date=October 26, 1917}}</ref>\n* The Italian military disaster at [[Battle of Caporetto|Caporetto]], [[Italy]] lead to the fall of the [[Paolo Boselli]] government.<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1917/10/27/102371170.pdf Italian Cabinet Resigns Office; Beaten on Vote of Confidence Thursday, the Boselli Ministry Retires], The New York Times, October 27, 1917</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Passchendaele]] &ndash; British and Canadian forces attacked defensive ridges east of the village of [[Passendale|Passchendaele]], [[Belgium]] that the [[Allies of World War I|Allies]] failed to take earlier in the month.<ref>{{cite book| series=Official History of the Canadian Army in the First World War |title=Canadian Expeditionary Force 1914\u20131919 |last=Nicholson |first=G. W. L. |authorlink = G. W. L. Nicholson |year=1962 |publisher=Queen's Printer and Controller of Stationery |location=Ottawa |url=http://www.cmp-cpm.forces.gc.ca/dhh-dhp/his/docs/CEF_e.pdf |accessdate=23 March 2014 |oclc=59609928|pages=318\u2013320}}</ref>\n* The [[U.S. Army]] established the [[2nd Infantry Division (United States)|2nd Infantry Division]] which included the [[3rd Infantry Brigade, 2nd Infantry Division|3rd Infantry Brigade]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/forcestruc/cbtchron/cc/002id.htm|title=Lineage and Honors Information: 2nd Infantry Division |publisher=[[United States Army Center of Military History]] |accessdate=3 November 2009}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Mario Biaggi]], American politician, [[U.S. Representative]] from [[New York (state)|New York]] from 1969 to 1988, in [[New York City]] (d. [[2015]])\n\n== [[October 27]], 1917 (Saturday) ==\n* [[Battle of La Malmaison]] &ndash; The [[Sixth Army (France)|French Sixth Army]] captured the [[Pinon, Aisne|Pinon]] commune and the surrounding forest from the Germans in northern [[France]], thus liberating the village and fort of [[La Malmaison]], [[France]] from German control.{{sfn|Times|1918|pp=245-246}} French losses were 2,241 killed, 8,162 wounded and 1,460 missing. However, French forces captured 11,157 German prisoners and 1,100 machine gun, artillery and mortar pieces.<ref>{{cite book|last=Doughty |first=R. A. |title=Pyrrhic victory: French Strategy and Operations in the Great War |location=Cambridge, MA |publisher=The Belknap Press of Harvard University |year=2005 |isbn=978-0-674-01880-8|pages=384\u2013389}}</ref> German losses were estimated at 38,000 killed or missing.<ref>{{cite book |title=Attriotin: Fighting the First World War |last=Philpott |first=W. |authorlink= |year=2014 |publisher=Little, Brown |location=London |edition= |isbn=978-1-4087-0355-7|page=279}}</ref>\n* [[Third Battle of Gaza]] &ndash; British and French naval vessels bombarded [[Gaza City|Gaza]] to soften Ottoman defensive prior to infantry assault on November 1. An Ottoman aircraft strafed one of the British ships, killing 38 sailors.<ref>{{cite book |title=Military Operations: Egypt & Palestine from June 1917 to the End of the War |last=Falls |first=Cyril |series=Official History of the Great War Based on Official Documents by Direction of the Historical Section of the Committee of Imperial Defence |others=A. F. Becke (maps) |year=1930 |volume=Volume 2 Part I |publisher=HM Stationery Office |location=London|oclc=644354483|pages=65\u201366}}</ref> \n* [[Battle of Buqqar Ridge]] &ndash; The [[Desert Mounted Corps]] repelled an [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] attack on its garrison at el Buqqar Ridge, [[Syria]] during the last days of the [[Stalemate in Southern Palestine]].<ref>Falls 1930, p.37</ref>\n* British flying ace [[Arthur Rhys-Davids]] disappeared while pursuing a German squadron east of [[Roeselare]], [[Belgium]]. His death wasn't confirmed until December 29 when German command informed he had been shot down by German flying ace [[Karl Gallwitz]]. At the time, he had been credited with 27 victories including German aces [[Carl Menckhoff]] and [[Werner Voss]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Revell|first1=Alex|title=Brief Glory: The Life of Arthur Rhys Davids, DSO, MC and Bar'|date=2010|publisher=Pen & Sword Aviation|location=Barnsley|isbn=978-1-84884-162-8|page=200}}</ref>\n* The [[Irish Volunteers]] held its convention immediately following the Sinn F\u00e9in convention, with most of the delegates having attended both. Newly-elected Sinn F\u00e9in president \u00c9amon de Valera was also elected president of the Volunteers.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Valiulis |first1=Maryann |title=Portrait of a Revolutionary: General Richard Mulcahy and the Founding of the Irish Free State |date=1992 |publisher=University Press of Kentucky |isbn=0-8131-1791-7 |page=24 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YGizfkDzVXEC&pg=PA24 |accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Oliver Tambo]], South African politician, President of the [[African National Congress]] from 1967 to 1991, in [[Nkantolo]], [[South Africa]] (d. [[1993]])\n\n== [[October 28]], 1917 (Sunday) ==\n* [[Switzerland]] held its [[1917 Swiss federal election|federal election]], with the [[Free Democratic Party of Switzerland]] retaining its majority in the [[National Council (Switzerland)|National Council]].<ref>[http://www.bfs.admin.ch/bfs/portal/fr/index/themen/17/22/lexi.Document.137139.xls Elections to the National Council 1848\u20131917: Distribution of seats by party or political orientation] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923230855/http://www.bfs.admin.ch/bfs/portal/fr/index/themen/17/22/lexi.Document.137139.xls |date=2015-09-23 }} BFS</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Passchendaele]] &ndash; The Canadian forces advance slowed due to German resistance but were able to hold the line for reinforcements, at a cost of 2,481 casualties.<ref>{{cite book|title=In Flanders Fields, Passchendaele 1917 |last=Wolff |first=L. |year=1979 |orig-year=1958 |publisher=Penguin |edition=reprint |location=London |isbn=978-0-14-004896-4|pages=247\u2013248}}</ref>\n* [[U.S. Army]] troopship {{USAT|Finland}} was torpedoed and damaged in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] off [[Brest, France]] by German submarine {{SMU|U-93||6}} with the loss of nine of her crew.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uboat.net/wwi/ships_hit/2179/.html |title=Finland |publisher=Uboat.net |accessdate=23 October 2012 }}{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] beat [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] 5-4 and 4-2 in the [[1917 All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship Final|All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship Final]] in [[Croke Park]], [[Dublin]].<ref>Corry, Eoghan, ''The GAA Book of Lists'' (Hodder Headline Ireland, 2005)</ref><ref>Donegan, Des, ''The Complete Handbook of Gaelic Games'' (DBA Publications Limited, 2005)</ref>\n* The historical romance ''[[The Woman God Forgot]]'', directed by [[Cecil B. DeMille]] and starring [[Geraldine Farrar]] in the title role, was released and became the fifth box office hit of the year. A copy of the film is in the [[George Eastman House Motion Picture Collection]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/W/WomanGodForgot1917.html |title=Progressive Silent Film List: ''The Woman God Forgot'' | accessdate=February 3, 2010|work=Silent Era}}</ref> \n* '''Born:''' [[Jack Soo]], American actor, best known for the role of Nick Yemana in the police television sitcom ''[[Barney Miller]]'', in [[Oakland, California]] (d. [[1979]]); [[Honor Frost]], Cyprus archaeologist, pioneer in [[underwater archaeology]], in [[Nicosia]], [[Cyprus]] (d. [[2010 in archaeology|2010]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Prince Christian of Schleswig-Holstein]], Danish-British noble, husband to [[Princess Helena of the United Kingdom]] (b. [[1831]]); [[Eugenio Elia Levi]], Italian mathematician, known for his contributions to [[group theory]], brother to [[Beppo Levi]] (killed in action) (b. [[1883]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Cecil Rawling]], British explorer, commander of expeditions to [[Tibet]] and [[Dutch New Guinea]] (killed during the [[Battle of Passchendaele]]) (b. [[1870]]); [[Isaac S. Taylor]], American architect, best known for his designs for key buildings in [[St. Louis]] (b. [[1850]])\n\n== [[October 29]], 1917 (Monday) ==\n* [[Battle of Pozzuolo]] &ndash; Two Italian brigades staged a rearguard action against the advancing German and Austrian forces at [[Pozzuolo del Friuli]], [[Italy]] as the [[Second Army (Italy)|Italian Second Army]] retreated from their disastrous defeat at the [[Battle of Caporetto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.difesa.it/Operazioni+Militari/operazioni+in+atto/Kosovo+-+JOINT+GUARDIAN/notizie-teatro-dettaglio.htm?solotesto=true&DetailID=2345|title=Sito del Ministero della Difesa, url consultato il 1/3/2009}}</ref>\n* Three German ''[[Luftstreitkr\u00e4fte]]'' (German Air Force) bombers set out for the first [[heavier-than-air]] night raid on [[England]] in four weeks. Two of the bombers diverted to [[Calais]], [[France]] due to bad weather, but the third reached [[England]] and bombed the [[Essex]] coast.<ref>Fredette 1976, pp. 162-166.</ref>\n* The [[U.S. Army]] established the [[92nd Infantry Division (United States)|92nd Infantry Division]].<ref>{{cite web|title=92nd Infantry Division| url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/forcestruc/cbtchron/cc/092id.htm|publisher=U.S. Army Center of Military History|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref>\n* The [[Merriwa railway line]] in [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]] was completed.<ref>'''''A Short History of the Muswellbrook - Merriwa Branch Line''''' Preston, R.G. [[Australian Railway History|Australian Railway Historical Society Bulletin]], October, 1967 pp. 205-214.</ref>\n* [[Roscoe Arbuckle|Roscoe \"Fatty\" Arbuckle]] and [[Buster Keaton]] starred in the film comedy ''[[Coney Island (1917 film)|Coney Island]]''.<ref>{{cite book| last=Knopf|first=Robert|title=The theater and cinema of Buster Keaton|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fU5qDx7tawIC&pg=PA180|accessdate=21 October 2010|date=August 2, 1999|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-00442-6|page=180}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Eddie Constantine]], American actor, best known for the role of [[Lemmy Caution]], most notably in the [[French New Wave]] science fiction film ''[[Alphaville (film)|Alphaville]]'', in [[Los Angeles]] (d. [[1993]]); [[Harold Garfinkel]], American sociologist, developed [[ethnomethodology]] as a field of inquiry for social behavior, in [[Newark, New Jersey]] (d. [[2011]])\n\n== [[October 30]], 1917 (Tuesday) ==\n* [[Vittorio Emanuele Orlando]] replaced [[Paolo Boselli]] as [[Prime Minister of Italy]] and continued in that role through the rest of the war.<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1917/10/31/102373098.pdf Invasion Cements Italian Unity; All Factions in Accord in Supporting a Vigorous Fighting Policy. Orlando Is Now Premier], The New York Times, October 31, 1917</ref>\n* [[Battle of Caporetto]] &ndash; After delaying a decision for five days despite pressure from his officers, Italian General [[Luigi Cadorna]] relented and ordered the [[Second Army (Italy)|Italian Second Army]] to retreat back to the [[Tagliamento]] River.<ref>Stearns & Langer 2001, p. 669</ref> Meanwhile, the two Italian brigades assigned to protect the rear were destroyed by the German and Austrian forces at the [[Battle of Pozzuolo]].<ref>Ministero della Difesa 2009</ref>\n* [[Second Battle of Passchendaele]] &ndash; Canadian forces advanced {{convert|600|yd|m|abbr=on}} from the starting line, capturing key defense positions around the hamlets of Meetcheele and Goudberg, [[Belgium]] at the cost of {{nowrap|2,321 casualties}}.{{sfn|Nicholson|1962|pp=322\u2013323}}\n* [[Charles Stewart (1868\u20131946)|Charles Stewart]] became [[Premier of Alberta]], replacing [[Arthur Sifton]] who had been chosen to be the provincial representative of the federal [[Unionist Party (Canada)|Unionist coalition]] in [[Ottawa]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Lewis Gwynne |last=Thomas |title=The Liberal Party in Alberta |url=https://archive.org/details/liberalpartyinal0000thom |url-access=registration |year=1959 |publisher=University of Toronto Press |location=[[Toronto]], Ontario}}</ref>\n* Twenty-two German [[Gotha]] bombers set out to raid [[London]], with the newly developed 4.5-kg (9.9-lb) [[incendiary bomb]] included in their bomb loads. Fewer than half the bombers reached the London area, and many of the incendiary bombs failed to ignite for the bomb drops that were delivered. The remaining planes bombed [[Kent]], destroying a [[Gas holder|gasometer]] in [[Ramsgate]] but achieving little else. Five of the bombers crashed while attempting to land upon returning to their bases. Bad weather prevented further raids against England until December.<ref>Fredette 1976, pp. 162-166</ref>\n* German [[flying ace]] [[Lieutenant]] [[Heinrich Gontermann]] was performing aerobatics when the upper wing of his [[Fokker Dr.I]] fighter broke off, causing him to crash where he died from injuries. He had 39 victories, tying him with [[Lieutenant]] [[Carl Menckhoff]] as the 13th-highest-scoring German ace of [[World War One]].<ref>Franks, Norman, ''Aircraft Versus Aircraft: The Illustrated Story of Fighter Pilot Combat From 1914 to the Present Day'', London: Grub Street, 1998, {{ISBN|1-902304-04-7}}, p. 63.</ref>\n* The [[\u00c9cole sup\u00e9rieure d'optique|Institut d'optique Graduate School]] was established as a post-secondary school for the field of optics in [[France]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Creation|url=https://www.institutoptique.fr/Institut/Presentation/Histoire/L-histoire-de-l-Institut-d-Optique-la-creation|website=\u00c9cole sup\u00e9rieure d'optique|accessdate=9 April 2017|language=French}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Maurice Trintignant]], French race car driver, member of the [[Formula One]] circuit from 1950 to 1964, winner of the [[1954 24 Hours of Le Mans]] race, in [[Sainte-C\u00e9cile-les-Vignes]], [[France]] (d. [[2005]]); [[Anna Marly]], Russian-French singer and songwriter, known for protest and political songs including \"[[Chant des Partisans]]\" and \"La complainte du partisan\", in [[Saint Petersburg]] (d. [[2006]]) \n* '''Born:''' [[Bobby Bragan]], American baseball player, catcher and shortstop for the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] and [[History of the Brooklyn Dodgers|Brooklyn Dodgers]] from 1940 and 1948, in [[Birmingham, Alabama]] (b. [[2010]]); [[Robert Maheu]], American business executive, CEO of [[Nevada]] operations for [[Howard Hughes]], author of ''Next to Hughes: Behind the Power and Tragic Downfall of Howard Hughes by His Closest Advisor'', in [[Waterville, Maine]] (d. [[2008]])\n* '''Died:''' [[Alex Decoteau]], Canadian-Cree athlete and law enforcer, first indigenous police officer in [[Canada]], track and field representative for [[Canada]] at the [[1912 Summer Olympics]] (killed at the [[Second Battle of Passchendaele]]) (b. [[1887]])\n\n== [[October 31]], 1917 (Wednesday) ==\n* [[Battle of Beersheba (1917)|Battle of Beersheba]] &ndash; The British [[XX Corps (United Kingdom)|XX Corps]] and [[Desert Mounted Corps]] of the [[Egyptian Expeditionary Force]] attacked and captured [[Beersheba]], [[Syria]], from Ottoman forces, ending the [[stalemate in Southern Palestine]] and starting the [[Southern Palestine Offensive]]. Some 1,947 Ottoman troops were taken prisoner and another estimated 1,000 were killed or wounded. British casualties were 171 killed.<ref>{{cite book|last=Grainger|first=John D.|year=2006|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3SVvryoR2A0C|title=The Battle for Palestine, 1917|location=Woodbridge|publisher=Boydell Press|isbn=978-1-843-83263-8|oclc=255698307|page=121}}</ref> The capture of [[Beersheba]] was clinched with a rare (by this date) mounted [[Charge (warfare)|charge]] by the [[Australian Mounted Division]].<ref>12th Light Horse Regiment War Diary October 1917 AWM4-10-17-9</ref><ref>4th Light Horse Regiment War Diary October 1917 AWM4-10-9-34</ref> \n* Real estate services company [[Cushman & Wakefield]] was established in [[New York City]] by brothers-in-law J. Clydesdale Cushman and Bernard Wakefield. The firm now operates in 60 countries and employs more than 43,000 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/books/politics-and-business-magazines/cushman-wakefield-inc|title=Cushman & Wakefield |publisher=Encyclopedia.com |date=2006 |accessdate=2017-02-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/houston/print-edition/2015/05/15/acquisition-next-step-in-cushman-wakefield-s.html |title=Acquisition next step in Cushman & Wakefield's storied history|publisher=Houston Business Journal |date=2015-05-15 |accessdate=2015-02-07}}</ref>\n* '''Born:''' [[Patience Gray]], British writer, known for best-selling cook and travel books including ''Plats Du Jour'' and ''Honey From A Weed'', in [[Shackleford]], [[England]] (d. [[2005]]); [[Bruce Bennett (politician)|Bruce Bennett]], American politician, [[Attorney General]] of [[Arkansas]] from 1957 to 1960, in [[Helena, Arkansas]] (d. [[1979]])\n* '''Born:''' [[Evan Mackie]], New Zealand air force officer, commander of the [[No. 92 Squadron RAF|No. 92]] and [[No. 80 Squadron RAF|No. 80 Squadron]] during [[World War Two]], recipient of the [[Distinguished Service Order]] and two [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Crosses]] from both the [[United Kingdom]] and [[United States]], in [[Waihi]], [[New Zealand]] (d. [[1986]]); [[Gordon Steege]], Australian air force officer, held various commands during [[World War Two]] including [[No. 3 Squadron RAAF|No. 3 Squadron]], recipient of the [[Distinguished Service Order]] and the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Flying Cross]], in [[Chatswood, New South Wales]], [[Australia]] (d. [[2013]])\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Events by month links}}\n\n[[Category:October|1917]]\n[[Category:1917|*1917-10]]\n[[Category:Months in the 1910s|*1917-10]]\n", "name_user": "Onco p53", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, replaced: Ngaruawahia \u2192 Ng\u0101ruaw\u0101hia   as perWikipedia:Naming_conventions_(New_Zealand)and https://gazetteer.linz.govt.nz/place/32480,typo(s) fixed: long distance \u2192 long-distance, 1-0 \u2192 1\u20130 (2), \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/October_1917"}
{"title_page": "Kyrkok\u00f6pinge Church", "text_new": "[[File:Kyrkok\u00f6pinge kyrka sedd fr\u00e5n syd\u00f6st.JPG|thumb|Kyrkok\u00f6pinge Church ]]\n'''Kyrkok\u00f6pinge Church''' ({{lang-sv|Kyrkok\u00f6pinge kyrka}}) is a medieval [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] church just outside [[Trelleborg]], Sweden. It belongs to the [[Diocese of Lund]].\n\n==History and architecture==\nThe oldest parts of Kyrkok\u00f6pinge Church are the [[nave]], [[choir (architecture)|choir]] and [[apse]], dating from the 12th century.<ref name=dk2>{{cite web |url= http://www.dalkopingeforsamling.se/kyrkorna/kyrkokopinge%20hemsida/kyrkokopinge.htm|title= Kyrkok\u00f6pinge kyrka|language=Swedish|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= |publisher= Dalk\u00f6pinge parish (Church of Sweden)|accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=ssl>{{cite web |url= http://www.soderslattsmuseer.se/sv/poi/47|title= Kyrkok\u00f6pinge kyrka|language=Swedish|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= www.soderslattsmuseer.se|publisher= S\u00f6dersl\u00e4tts museer|accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref> The master craftsman responsible for the building project was either M\u00e5rten stenm\u00e4stare  known to have worked on the construction site of [[Lund Cathedral]], or his pupil, the known as Oxiem\u00e4staren. This can be deducted from the [[baptismal font]] of the church, which is original and bears the markings of both craftsmen.<ref name=ssl/> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://sok.riksarkivet.se/Sbl/Presentation.aspx?id=8642|title=M\u00e5rten\n|website=  Svenskt biografiskt lexikon|access-date=December 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe building material is whitewashed [[fieldstone]], except for some of the more important details, which are of [[limestone]].<ref name=dk2/> At the beginning of the 13th century, a tower was added to the church.<ref name=ssl/> Sometime during the [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] era, [[crow-stepped gable]]s were added to the fa\u00e7ade.<ref name=trelleborg>{{cite web |url= http://www.trelleborg.se/sv/kommun-politik/kommunfakta/trelleborgs-historia/kyrkorna/kyrkokopinge-kyrka/|title= Dalk\u00f6pinge kyrka|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |language=Swedish|website= |publisher= Trelleborg Municipality|accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref> During the 15th century an original wooden ceiling was replaced by brick vaults, and during the same century a [[church porch]] was added.<ref name=ssl/>\n\n==Interior==\nThe church interior is partly decorated with [[mural]]s, dating from the end of the 15th century. The paintings depict religious subjects: [[Book of Genesis|Genesis]], the [[Last Judgment]] and a number of saints. Among the furnishings, the [[triumphal cross]] is an example of medieval sculpture in a transitional style between [[Romanesque art|Romanesque]] and [[Gothic art]]. The aforementioned baptismal font is decoratively sculptured with vines and a lion. The [[altarpiece]] dates from 1631. The [[pulpit]] is possibly from the same time.<ref name=ssl/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.dalkopingeforsamling.se/kyrkorna/kyrkokopinge%20hemsida/kyrkokopinge.htm Official site (in Swedish)]\n \n{{commons category| Kyrkok\u00f6pinge kyrka}}\n{{coord|55|23|06|N|13|11|10|E|type:landmark_region:SE|display=title}}\n\n{{Churches in Scania}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kyrkokopinge Church}}\n[[Category:Churches in Sk\u00e5ne County]]\n[[Category:Churches in the Diocese of Lund]]\n[[Category:Churches converted from the Roman Catholic Church to the Church of Sweden]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Kyrkok\u00f6pinge kyrka sedd fr\u00e5n syd\u00f6st.JPG|thumb|Kyrkok\u00f6pinge Church ]]\n'''Kyrkok\u00f6pinge Church''' ({{lang-sv|Kyrkok\u00f6pinge kyrka}}) is a medieval [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] church just outside [[Trelleborg]], Sweden. It belongs to the [[Diocese of Lund]].\n\n==History and architecture==\nThe oldest parts of Kyrkok\u00f6pinge Church are the [[nave]], [[choir (architecture)|choir]] and [[apse]], dating from the 12th century.<ref name=dk2>{{cite web |url= http://www.dalkopingeforsamling.se/kyrkorna/kyrkokopinge%20hemsida/kyrkokopinge.htm|title= Kyrkok\u00f6pinge kyrka|language=Swedish|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= |publisher= Dalk\u00f6pinge parish (Church of Sweden)|accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref><ref name=ssl>{{cite web |url= http://www.soderslattsmuseer.se/sv/poi/47|title= Kyrkok\u00f6pinge kyrka|language=Swedish|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website= www.soderslattsmuseer.se|publisher= S\u00f6dersl\u00e4tts museer|accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref> The master craftsman responsible for the building project was either M\u00e5rten stenm\u00e4stare  known to have worked on the construction site of [[Lund Cathedral]], or his pupil, the known as Oxiem\u00e4staren. This can be deducted from the [[baptismal font]] of the church, which is original and bears the markings of both craftsmen.<ref name=ssl/> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://sok.riksarkivet.se/Sbl/Presentation.aspx?id=8642|title=M\u00e5rten\n|website=  Svenskt biografiskt lexikon|access-date=December 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe building material is whitewashed [[fieldstone]], except for some of the more important details, which are of [[limestone]].<ref name=dk2/> At the beginning of the 13th century, a tower was added to the church.<ref name=ssl/> Sometime during the [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] era, [[crow-stepped gable]]s were added to the fa\u00e7ade.<ref name=trelleborg>{{cite web |url= http://www.trelleborg.se/sv/kommun-politik/kommunfakta/trelleborgs-historia/kyrkorna/kyrkokopinge-kyrka/|title= Dalk\u00f6pinge kyrka|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |language=Swedish|website= |publisher= Trelleborg Municipality|accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref> During the 15th century an original wooden ceiling was replaced by brick vaults, and during the same century a [[church porch]] was added.<ref name=ssl/>\n\n==Interior==\nThe church interior is partly decorated with [[mural]]s, dating from the end of the 15th century. The paintings depict religious subjects: [[Genesis]], the [[Last Judgment]] and a number of saints. Among the furnishings, the [[triumphal cross]] is an example of medieval sculpture in a transitional style between [[Romanesque art|Romanesque]] and [[Gothic art]]. The aforementioned baptismal font is decoratively sculptured with vines and a lion. The [[altarpiece]] dates from 1631. The [[pulpit]] is possibly from the same time.<ref name=ssl/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.dalkopingeforsamling.se/kyrkorna/kyrkokopinge%20hemsida/kyrkokopinge.htm Official site (in Swedish)]\n \n{{commons category| Kyrkok\u00f6pinge kyrka}}\n{{coord|55|23|06|N|13|11|10|E|type:landmark_region:SE|display=title}}\n\n{{Churches in Scania}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kyrkokopinge Church}}\n[[Category:Churches in Sk\u00e5ne County]]\n[[Category:Churches in the Diocese of Lund]]\n[[Category:Churches converted from the Roman Catholic Church to the Church of Sweden]]\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Genesis", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kyrkok%C3%B6pinge_Church"}
